"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756895","Department of Health","false","2017-09-12","<p>There are no circumstances in which sodium chlorite or bleach, sometimes described as Miracle Mineral Solution (MMS), enemas should be used as a treatment to cure autism. We have been clear that MMS, or similar or related compounds, have no proven or conceivable health benefit and can cause serious damage to health, particularly in the case of children.</p><p> </p><p>Where there is any threat to the safety and wellbeing of a child, this may lead to offences of child cruelty being considered, requiring a wider safeguarding response involving the police, children's services and relevant partners. Such a threat could include any harm caused by the administration of a potentially noxious substance. Each case would be judged on its merits.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has received a limited amount of correspondence in relation to the use of bleach enemas as a treatment to cure autism.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","7786","2017-09-12T16:14:32.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756895/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756895/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756895/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-04","Miracle Mineral Solution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what representations he has received on the practice of bleach enema as a treatment to cure autism.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","7787"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756896","Home Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The table below sets out the substances identified as being used in attacks between November 2016 and April 2017 based on the returns from 39 police forces as part of the National Police Chiefs’ Council commissioned voluntary data collection.</p><p>Indicative figures for 408 acid or corrosive attacks broken down by substance</p><table><tbody><tr><td>Acid</td><td>56</td></tr><tr><td>Ammonia</td><td>69</td></tr><tr><td>Bleach</td><td>71</td></tr><tr><td>Other stated substance</td><td>107</td></tr><tr><td>Unknown liquid</td><td>74</td></tr><tr><td>No information provided</td><td>31</td></tr><tr><td>Total</td><td>408</td></tr></tbody></table><p>Other stated substance included a range of diverse substances including boiling water, lighter fluid, petrol, CS and pepper spray and non-ammonia/bleach household cleaning products.</p><p>These figures must be treated with caution, as they are not official statistics. Furthermore, they are only available for cases where the substance was recorded by officers and reflect what the officers involved in the case believed the substance to be, based on the available evidence.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-09-12T15:26:22.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756896/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756896/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756896/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-04","Crimes of Violence: Corrosive Substances","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 26 July 2017 to Question 5949, on crimes of violence: acids, how many of the assaults identified involved (a) acid, (b) ammonia, (c) bleach and (d) other substances.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","8124"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756897","Home Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The carrying or possession of acid or other corrosive substances is already an offence under section 1 of the Prevention of Crime Act 1953 if it can be proved that it is intended to cause injury. The Crown Prosecution Service has published guidance to this effect.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-09-12T14:10:33.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756897/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756897/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756897/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-04","Crimes of Violence: Acids","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans she has to update guidance to classify acid as a weapon made for causing injury under section 1 of the Prevention of Crime Act 1953.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","8147"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756898","Home Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The police have the power under section 59 of the Police Reform Act 2002 to seize any vehicle, including an off-road vehicle, used in a careless and inconsiderate manner or in a manner causing alarm, distress or annoyance to members of the public. The Home Office does not collect or hold information on the number of seized vehicles.</p><p>The rules and guidance to the police on the recording of all crimes involving vehicles are set out in the National Crime Recording Standard and Home Office Counting Rules.</p><p>Home Office Ministers and officials have regular discussions on a wide range of topics with those representing the interests of police officers, including those representing specialist police drivers.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","8117 ; 8118 ; 8119","2017-09-12T10:50:53.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756898/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756898/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756898/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-04","Motorcycles: Seized Articles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many (a) motorcycles, (b) mopeds and (c) off-road vehicles have been seized by police under section 59 of the Police Reform Act 2002 in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","8148"
