"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758037","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Government is monitoring a wide range of economic indicators, including trends in company incorporation. There has been no significant change in those trends since the EU referendum. Statistics published by the Irish Companies Registration Office show that new company registrations in Ireland were around 22,000 in the year to August 2017, very similar to the rate before the referendum.</p><p>The UK’s decision to leave the EU means there will be a period of adjustment, but the UK economy is resilient. The unemployment rate is at its lowest level in four decades and the employment rate has never been higher. Businesses have continued to show their confidence in the UK, with major investments announced by GlaxoSmithKline, Google and Apple, among others.</p><p>Indeed, only last week Aston Martin announced a £500m trade and investment deal between the United Kingdom and Japan which will, amongst other things, benefit its plant in St Athan in Vale of Glamorgan.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-09-07T16:25:53.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758037/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758037/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758037/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-08-29","Companies: Registration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what discussions he has had with Cabinet colleagues on (a) the total number and (b) trends in the number of UK companies choosing to register in Ireland as a result of the UK's decision to leave the EU; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Geraint Davies","Swansea West","Geraint Davies","900654"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758509","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-09-07","<p>DExEU ministers regularly discuss exit issues with Cabinet and Ministerial colleagues. This includes security. <br><br>The Prime Minister has been clear that we will continue to work closely with our European partners to tackle a range of security issues.<br><br>The safety of the British public is a top priority. That security is enhanced through cooperating with Europe. The UK has always been, and will continue to be, a major global player in the fight against threats to security. <br><br>With the threat constantly evolving, our response must be to work more closely with our partners, including the EU and its Member States, sharing information and supporting each other in combating the threats posed by those who wish us harm.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-09-07T15:40:54.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758509/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758509/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758509/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-08-29","National Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what discussions he has had with Cabinet colleagues on ensuring future cooperation with the EU on security policy after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Luke Hall","Thornbury and Yate","Luke Hall","900656"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758510","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Secretary of State raised this matter most recently in the last plenary session of the negotiations.<br> <br>There have not yet been any formal negotiations on transition. The UK Government has repeatedly made clear our intent to agree implementation provisions. As outlined in the Northern Ireland and Ireland Position Paper, Privileges and Immunities Position Paper, and Customs Future Relationship Paper (see attached extracts).</p><p>This will allow people and businesses in both the UK and the EU to adjust in a smooth and orderly way to new arrangements, and to be able to plan for the future. It will help both sides to minimise disruption if we agree this principle early in the process, and we are ready to begin discussions on the form these provisions might take.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-09-07T16:24:42.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758510/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758510/answer","Position Paper extracts.pdf","Position Paper extracts.pdf","Position Paper extracts","Position Paper extracts","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/758510/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-08-29","UK Trade with EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what discussions he has had during negotiations with the EU on a transition period between the UK leaving the EU and the start date of a new trade agreement between the UK and the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Pat McFadden","Wolverhampton South East","Mr Pat McFadden","900657"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754481","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>The Cabinet Office has not publicly consulted on Civil Service pay levels in the last 12 months.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-05T13:42:33.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754481/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754481/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754481/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-20","Civil Servants: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the Government has received the results of any consultation on Civil Service pay levels in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","6449"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754482","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>I refer my Hon Friend to the answer I gave to the Hon. Member for Edinburgh North and Leith on 18 July 2017 to UIN: 4273.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-05T13:44:56.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754482/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754482/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754482/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-20","Government Departments: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what proportion of Government purchasing currently comes from small and medium-sized enterprises.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","6494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754483","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-09-05T13:16:13.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754483/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754483/answer","PQ6673.pdf","PQ6673.pdf","UKSA Response to PQ6673","UKSA Response to PQ6673","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754483/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-20","Public Sector: Jarrow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many and what proportion of people in Jarrow constituency worked in the public sector in each year for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Mr Stephen Hepburn","Jarrow","Mr Stephen Hepburn","6673"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754484","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>Voting more than once at a General Election or at other national polls such as a referendum is a crime which carries a financial penalty.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>We take this matter very seriously. I have raised this issue as a priority with the Electoral Commission, and will consider carefully the findings of their report on electoral registration at the 2017 General Election, as well as their upcoming report on the administration of that poll.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>It is possible to determine whether an individual has voted twice at a General Election by checking the marked register of those who have voted. If anyone has evidence of someone voting twice, then they should report this to their local returning officer and to the police.</p><p> </p><p>I have also written to the National Police Chiefs' Council (NPCC) to reiterate the Government's support for the police to make every effort to investigate reports of criminal behaviour in relation to elections.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will continue to consider if further steps should be taken to ensure the integrity of the electoral system and where opportunities could exist to reiterate that voting more than once at the General Election or other national polls is illegal.</p><p> </p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-09-05T13:26:57.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754484/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754484/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754484/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-20","Voting Behaviour","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps he is taking to ensure people can vote only once in an election.","false","Biography information for Jo Churchill","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill","6701"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754485","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>The Government stated in its manifesto its intention to repeal the Fixed-term Parliaments Act. Under the Act, the Prime Minister will make arrangements in 2020 for committee to carry out a review of the operation of the Act and, if appropriate, to make recommendations for its repeal or amendment. The Government believes that it is right for the committee to review the operation of the Act, before repealing it, to inform decisions about the nature of the repeal.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-09-05T13:31:16.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754485/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754485/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754485/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-20","Fixed-Term Parliaments Act 2011","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will seek to repeal the Fixed Terms Parliament Act 2011.","false","Biography information for Stephanie Peacock","Barnsley East","Stephanie Peacock","6705"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754486","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-11","<p>I refer the honourable gentlemen to my <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=QuestionsWithAnswersOnly&amp;house=commons&amp;uin=2583" target="_blank">written answer</a> on 11 July 2017 (UIN 2583) which outlines the eight location principles which HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) used to select its regional centres.</p><p>HMRC assessed both Leeds and Bradford with regards to these location principles, and chose Leeds as the location for the regional hub because it satisfied the principles more comprehensively overall.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-09-11T16:02:05.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754486/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754486/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754486/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Revenue and Customs: Yorkshire and the Humber","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the cost of having the HM Revenue and Customs regional hub for Yorkshire in (a) Leeds and (b) Bradford.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","6755"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754487","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-06","<p>The Treasury has not received any representations or reports on an increase in discrimination. UK Finance, the main industry trade body for this sector, have confirmed that mortgage lenders intend to pursue a business-as-usual approach throughout the withdrawal negotiation period, and will continue to treat customers fairly and act in the best interests of customers. Lenders are not currently adopting any changes to their lending criteria regarding citizenship status.</p><p>The Government’s objective is to provide reassurance and certainty to the 3 million EU citizens living in the UK. Negotiations with the EU have been constructive, and will consider the issue of economic rights at the next round of negotiations.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-09-06T10:05:03.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754487/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754487/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754487/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Mortgages: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he has received (a) representations or (b) reports on an increase in discrimination towards non-UK EU nationals in terms of their access to mortgage financing on account of uncertainty as to the future status of EU citizens; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","6828"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754488","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-06","<p>The Treasury has not made an assessment of the potential occurrence of discrimination in access to mortgages for non-UK EU citizens. UK Finance, the main industry trade body for this sector, have confirmed that mortgage lenders intend to pursue a business-as-usual approach throughout the withdrawal negotiation period, and will continue to treat customers fairly and act in the best interests of customers. Lenders are not currently adopting any changes to their lending criteria regarding citizenship status.</p><p>The Government’s objective is to provide reassurance and certainty to the 3 million EU citizens living in the UK. Negotiations with the EU have been constructive, and will consider the issue of economic rights at the next round of negotiations.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-09-06T10:06:11.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754488/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754488/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754488/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Mortgages: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he has made an assessment of the potential occurrence of discrimination in access to mortgages for non-UK EU citizens; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","6829"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754489","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-11","<p>As of June 2017, HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) had a headcount of 67,421 paid staff and employed a further 497 contractors. The contractors therefore represent 0.74% of the combined headcount. These figures do not include contractors working for Revenue and Customs Digital Technology Services, or external service suppliers who provide IT or other services to HMRC.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-09-11T16:00:30.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754489/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754489/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754489/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Revenue and Customs: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what proportion of staff at HM Revenue and Customs are employed on a sub-contractual basis.","false","Biography information for Jo Churchill","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill","6702"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754490","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-07","<p>The decision not to increase transparency in foreign exchange pricing is consistent with the Government’s approach to transposing other EU Directives, which is not to gold-plate and go beyond the requirements of the Directive wherever possible.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-09-07T16:05:06.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754490/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754490/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754490/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Foreign Exchange","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether his Department's decision not to gold-plate the Payment Services Regulations by increasing transparency in foreign exchange pricing is consistent with the Government's stated approach to gold-plating; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","6665"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754491","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-06","<p>It is the responsibility of the relevant departments and employers to consider how to distribute the funds available for their annual pay awards.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-09-06T13:42:40.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754491/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754491/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754491/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Public Sector: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what distributional analysis his Department has carried out on the pay of public sector workers who are not covered by a pay review body; and if he will place in the Library a copy of that analysis.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","6556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754492","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Government did not include a requirement in the Payment Services Regulations 2017 (PSRs) for increased transparency as it had to weigh up the potential benefits of doing so against other issues, such as the Government’s approach to implementing maximum harmonising Directives. The Government encourages all firms to bear in mind the recitals of the second Payment Services Directive and operate within the spirit of the Directive.</p><p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) is the regulatory body responsible for enforcing the PSRs. As part of ensuring that firms comply with the specific requirements of the Regulations, the Government is extending the FCA's rule-making powers to allow them to, among other things, make rules on financial promotions for payment institutions and e-money institutions.</p><p>On 19 July 2017 the FCA clarified concerns it has about some firms' misleading use of currency converter tools in relation to their currency transfer services. It announced plans to consult on making new rules within this market using the extended powers.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-09-07T16:07:14.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754492/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754492/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754492/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Payments: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Government response to the consultation on the Payment Services Regulations, what steps his Department will take to (a) bear in mind the disclosure requirements listed in recital 84 of the Payment Services Directive and (b) achieve greater transparency.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","6664"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754493","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-08","<p>It is the responsibility of the relevant departments to consider how to distribute the funds available for their annual pay awards.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-09-08T12:50:44.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754493/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754493/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754493/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Public Sector: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what distributional analysis his Department has carried out on the public sector pay cap; and if he will place in the Library a copy of that analysis.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","6553"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754494","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-06","<p>Central Government does not play a role in the pay negotiation process for firefighters. It is the responsibility of the National Joint Council (NJC) to consider what pay award is appropriate, taking into account views of fire and rescue authorities and the budgets available.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-09-06T13:38:46.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754494/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754494/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754494/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Fire and Rescue Services: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how the Government's estimates for 2017-18 as set out in the Supply and Appropriations (Main Estimates) 2010 will accommodate any increased pay offer to the Fire and Rescue Services.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","6554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754495","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-06","<p>It is the responsibility of relevant departments to consider equalities implications for their workforces.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-09-06T13:39:40.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754495/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754495/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754495/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Public Sector: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what equality impact assessment his Department has carried out on the pay of public sector workers who are not covered by a pay review body; and if he will place in the Library a copy of that assessment.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","6555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754496","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-06","<p>The government has not conducted a full distributional analysis of cutting corporation tax to 17%. This is because there is insufficient data about the income distribution of corporate shareholders and uncertainty about the incidence of corporation tax.</p><p> </p><p>However, it is widely accepted, including by the Institute for Fiscal Studies, that a significant proportion of the burden of corporation tax is borne by workers and consumers, not just shareholders.</p><p> </p><p>As with all tax measures, the Government has published a tax information and impact note (TIIN) for this measure which provides our assessment that there are no equalities impacts.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","6563","2017-09-06T09:23:14.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754496/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754496/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754496/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Corporation Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what distributional analysis his Department has carried out on the Government's plan to cut corporation tax to 17 per cent by 2020.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","6564"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754497","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-06","The estimated effect on Exchequer revenue resulting from the reduction of capital gains tax (a) basic rate to 10 per cent and (b) main rate to 20 per cent excluding residential property and carried interest was published at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/508147/PU1912_Policy_Costings_FINAL3.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/508147/PU1912_Policy_Costings_FINAL3.pdf</a>.","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-09-06T08:53:38.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754497/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754497/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754497/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Capital Gains Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much revenue was lost to the Exchequer as a result of the reduction of capital gains tax (a) basic rate to 10 per cent and (b) main rate to 20 per cent excluding residential property and carried interest since that reduction was implemented.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","6565"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754498","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-06","<p>HM Treasury publishes distributional analysis of the cumulative impact of the Government’s tax, welfare, and public service spending decisions at each fiscal event, the latest of which can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/597473/impact_on_households_SB2017_web.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/597473/impact_on_households_SB2017_web.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>The Government publishes Tax Information and Impact notes (TIINs) for all tax policy changes. TIINs provide an explanation of the policy objective together with details of the tax impact on the Exchequer, the economy, individuals, businesses, civil society organisations, as well as any equality or other specific area of impact. All TIINs, including those for the Budget 2016 changes to Capital Gains Tax, can be found here:</p><p><strong><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/tax-information-and-impact-notes-tiins" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/tax-information-and-impact-notes-tiins</a> </strong></p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","6549 ; 6550 ; 6590","2017-09-06T09:00:33.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754498/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754498/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754498/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Capital Gains Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what equality impact assessment his Department has undertaken on the reduction of capital gains tax (a) basic rate to 10 per cent and (b) main rate to 20 per cent excluding on residential property and carried interest.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","6770"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754499","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-06","<p>Statistics on R&amp;D are collected and published annually by the Office of National Statistics. The latest data available shows that in 2015, expenditure on R&amp;D performed in the UK was £31.6 billion – its highest level on record. This is the equivalent of 1.7% GDP.</p><p>Government will spend an additional £2bn per year by 2020-21, around a 20% increase in total annual government R&amp;D spending. In addition to public investment in R&amp;D – each £1 of public expenditure on R&amp;D leverages an average of £1.36 of private investment across the economy – many other factors encourage private sector investment. These include our competitive tax system and business environment – the government also increased the rate of business R&amp;D tax credits, providing £2.45bn of relief to 21,000 business in 2014-15 – and our ongoing commitment to improving the nations skills, including in STEM subjects.</p><p>Information on international spending is published regularly by the OECD and the European Commission is available online. The government’s increased spending signals that the UK remains committed to being at the forefront of global science, research and innovation.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","6593 ; 6731","2017-09-06T13:37:48.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754499/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754499/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754499/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Research: Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans the Government has put in place to encourage private sector investment in research and development.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","6548"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754500","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-06","<p>HM Treasury publishes distributional analysis of the cumulative impact of the Government’s tax, welfare, and public service spending decisions at each fiscal event, the latest of which can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/597473/impact_on_households_SB2017_web.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/597473/impact_on_households_SB2017_web.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>The Government publishes Tax Information and Impact notes (TIINs) for all tax policy changes. TIINs provide an explanation of the policy objective together with details of the tax impact on the Exchequer, the economy, individuals, businesses, civil society organisations, as well as any equality or other specific area of impact. All TIINs, including those for the Budget 2016 changes to Capital Gains Tax, can be found here:</p><p><strong><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/tax-information-and-impact-notes-tiins" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/tax-information-and-impact-notes-tiins</a> </strong></p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","6550 ; 6590 ; 6770","2017-09-06T09:00:32.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754500/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754500/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754500/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Public Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what equality impact assessment his Department has carried out on the provisions of the forthcoming Finance Bill; and if he will place in the Library a copy of the relevant documents when that Bill receives its First Reading.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","6549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754501","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-06","<p>HM Treasury publishes distributional analysis of the cumulative impact of the Government’s tax, welfare, and public service spending decisions at each fiscal event, the latest of which can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/597473/impact_on_households_SB2017_web.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/597473/impact_on_households_SB2017_web.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>The Government publishes Tax Information and Impact notes (TIINs) for all tax policy changes. TIINs provide an explanation of the policy objective together with details of the tax impact on the Exchequer, the economy, individuals, businesses, civil society organisations, as well as any equality or other specific area of impact. All TIINs, including those for the Budget 2016 changes to Capital Gains Tax, can be found here:</p><p><strong><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/tax-information-and-impact-notes-tiins" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/tax-information-and-impact-notes-tiins</a> </strong></p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","6549 ; 6590 ; 6770","2017-09-06T09:00:33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754501/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754501/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754501/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Public Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what distributional analysis his Department has carried out on the forthcoming Finance Bill; and if he will place in the Library a copy of the relevant documents when that Bill receives First Reading.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","6550"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754502","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Government has previously consulted extensively on the impacts of abolishing Class 2 NICs and responded to this consultation at Autumn Statement. This response is available at https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/consultation-on-abolishing-class-2-national-insurance-and-introducing-a-contributory-benefit-test-to-class-4-national-insurance-for-the-self-employed. The Government published a tax information and impact note on this policy at Autumn Statement 2016.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","6587 ; 6588","2017-09-11T15:51:33.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754502/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754502/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754502/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","National Insurance Contributions: Self-employed","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when the Government plans to introduce legislative proposals for the abolition of Class 2s NICS as announced in the 2016 Budget.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","6551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754503","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-05","<p>The Government published its response to consultation on the Green Paper on <em>Corporate Governance Reform </em>on 29th August.</p><p>The response sets out the Government’s plans to introduce secondary legislation to require quoted companies to report annually the ratio of CEO pay to the average pay of their UK workforce along with a narrative explaining changes to that ratio from year to year and setting the ratio in the context of pay and conditions across the wider workforce.</p><p>Companies already face a binding vote on their executive remuneration policy at least once every three years, and must win a binding shareholder vote for any executive pay proposals that deviate from that policy. Most listed companies secure strong backing from their shareholders for their executive pay arrangements and are sensitive to shareholder concerns.</p><p>A minority, however, do not respond adequately to shareholder concerns. The Government has therefore invited the Financial Reporting Council to revise the UK Corporate Governance Code to be more specific about the steps that premium listed companies should take to understand and address shareholder concerns when they encounter significant opposition to their executive pay policies and awards.</p><p>The Government has also invited the Investment Association to implement a proposal made in its response to the Green Paper to maintain a public register of listed companies encountering shareholder opposition to pay awards of 20% or more. This will be accompanied by a record of what these companies have said they are doing to address shareholder concerns. The Government will monitor the impact of these measures.</p><p>A copy of the Government’s response to consultation on the <em>Corporate Governance Reform </em>green paper can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/corporate-governance-reform" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/corporate-governance-reform</a>.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","6496","2017-09-05T16:27:49.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754503/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754503/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754503/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-20","Directors: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will ensure that listed companies publish the ratio of executive pay to the average pay of the broader UK workforce.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","6495"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754504","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-05","<p>Treasury Ministers and officials have meetings with a wide variety of organisations in the public and private sectors as part of the process of policy development and delivery.</p><p> </p><p>Details of ministerial and permanent secretary meetings with external organisations on departmental business are published on a quarterly basis and are available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-ministers-meetings-hospitality-gifts-and-overseas-travel" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-ministers-meetings-hospitality-gifts-and-overseas-travel</a></p><p><strong><br> </strong></p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","6464","2017-09-05T07:45:46.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754504/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754504/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754504/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Saudi Aramco","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether, and on what date he or officials of his Department have met with representatives of the Government of Saudi Arabia to discuss the scheduled Saudi Aramco IPO in the last 24 months.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","6463"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754505","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-05","<p>The Government has undertaken an extensive programme of engagement with financial services firms since the referendum last year, in order to listen to and understand concerns from across the sector.</p><p> </p><p>This has included ministerial and official meetings with firms from the banking, asset management, insurance, pensions and market infrastructure industries.</p><p> </p><p>We have been clear that we are aiming for a deep relationship with our EU partners which will maintain as much of the current cross-border arrangements as possible.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-09-05T07:47:26.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754505/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754505/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754505/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Financial Institutions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what representations he has received from the financial services sector on whether financial institutions may leave the UK once the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","6465"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754507","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-06","<p>The government is investing approximately £1 billion in modernising our courts and tribunals, and improving the digital infrastructure for our criminal courts.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-09-06T13:41:51.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754507/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754507/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754507/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Courts: Modernisation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the cost of plans to modernise the courts system.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","6491"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754508","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-06","<p>EU law does not allow for the application of different VAT rates in different regions of the UK. VAT rates must therefore apply across the whole of the UK. The government has considered the economic costs and benefits of a reduced rate of VAT for tourism related activities and has concluded that there is currently insufficient evidence that this would provide value for money.</p><p> </p><p>The government will look again at the impact of both VAT and APD on tourism in Northern Ireland and will commission a detailed consultative report to gather further evidence to recommend how best to build upon the growing success of that sector.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-09-06T09:14:16.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754508/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754508/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754508/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Hotels and Restaurants: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans he has to reduce VAT on hotels and restaurants in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","6493"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754509","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-06","<p>Since 2010, the Government have secured almost £160 billion in additional tax revenue as a result of actions to tackle tax evasion, tax avoidance and non-compliance. This includes more than £2.7 billon from offshore tax evaders, with action both at home and abroad.</p><p> </p><p>The UK already has effective legislation to tackle avoidance involving offshore trusts. We announced our intention to legislate further, making it harder for anybody to avoid paying tax on funds held in offshore trusts and to introduce tougher sanctions for those who fail to declare past UK tax liabilities on offshore interests before October 2018. The Government is introducing legislation which will raise over £1.5bn from non-domiciled individuals over a five-year period.</p><p> </p><p>The UK has been at the forefront of international work which has seen over 100 countries commit to automatically exchange financial account information. Furthermore, we have set up a register for trusts with tax consequences, we have introduced new civil and criminal sanctions for offshore tax evaders and those who help them, and since 2010, we have invested over £1.8 billion in HMRC to tackle evasion, avoidance and non-compliance.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","6462 ; 6560","2017-09-06T09:25:34.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754509/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754509/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754509/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans he has to introduce measures to tackle tax avoidance and evasion by people through nom-dom status and offshore trusts.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","6461"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754510","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-06","<p>Since 2010, the Government have secured almost £160 billion in additional tax revenue as a result of actions to tackle tax evasion, tax avoidance and non-compliance. This includes more than £2.7 billon from offshore tax evaders, with action both at home and abroad.</p><p> </p><p>The UK already has effective legislation to tackle avoidance involving offshore trusts. We announced our intention to legislate further, making it harder for anybody to avoid paying tax on funds held in offshore trusts and to introduce tougher sanctions for those who fail to declare past UK tax liabilities on offshore interests before October 2018. The Government is introducing legislation which will raise over £1.5bn from non-domiciled individuals over a five-year period.</p><p> </p><p>The UK has been at the forefront of international work which has seen over 100 countries commit to automatically exchange financial account information. Furthermore, we have set up a register for trusts with tax consequences, we have introduced new civil and criminal sanctions for offshore tax evaders and those who help them, and since 2010, we have invested over £1.8 billion in HMRC to tackle evasion, avoidance and non-compliance.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","6461 ; 6560","2017-09-06T09:25:34.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754510/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754510/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754510/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Offshore Trusts: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the loss of revenue to the Exchequer as a result of (a) tax avoidance and (b) tax evasion by people and companies through offshore trusts in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","6462"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754511","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-05","<p>The Money Laundering, Terrorist Financing and Transfer of Funds (Information on the Payer) Regulations 2017 (MLRs) have implemented the EU’s 4th Money Laundering Directive (4MLD). The directive (and therefore the MLRs) is underpinned by the principles of effectiveness and proportionality as well as a continued focus on a risk-based approach. Therefore, the MLRs apply to only those sectors that are reasonably susceptible to the risks of money laundering and terrorist financing and that are seen as ‘gatekeepers’ to the financial system. In considering which sectors are susceptible and therefore higher or lower risk, this could mean looking at, for example, supervisory information on risks within the sector, any steps taken by industry to mitigate these risks, the level of law enforcement and any evidence submitted during government consultations.</p><p> </p><p>For more information on why the Government has decided to exclude certain sectors from the scope of the MLRs, please see the Government’s consultation response of March 2017:</p><p> </p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/money-laundering-regulations-2017/money-laundering-regulations-2017</p><p> </p><p>As per Regulation 16 of the MLRs, the Government will continue to identify and review the risks in relation to money laundering and terrorist financing with a view to mitigating those risks within the United Kingdom.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-09-05T10:15:48.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754511/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754511/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754511/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Money Laundering, Terrorist Financing and Transfer of
funds (Information on the Payer) Regulations 2017","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, on what evidential basis his Department has chosen to exclude from the scope of the Money Laundering, Terrorist Financing and Transfer of Funds (Information on the Payer) Regulations 2017 each type of business referred to.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","6448"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754512","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-11","<p>The OECD has found that cutting corporation taxes can increase GDP, and this is backed up by Government modelling in 2016 which estimated that cuts announced since 2010 could increase GDP by up to 1.3% in the long run. The increased profits, wages, employment and consumption that come with higher growth all feed through into higher tax revenues.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-09-11T16:02:21.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754512/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754512/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754512/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Corporation Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 28 June 2017 to Question 957, what the evidential basis is for the increase in corporation tax receipts referred to being directly attributable to reductions in the rate of corporation tax.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","6391"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754513","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-06","<p>The Government and the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) are committed to ensuring that savers and investors are treated fairly when they make investment decisions and are able to get the best outcomes from their investments.</p><p>The Government welcomes the FCA’s final report on their competition market study on the asset management sector.</p><p>We will be studying the final findings and remedies closely to see what the Government can do to support the regulator’s work and deliver the right outcomes for people who rely on their pension savings.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-09-06T09:15:17.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754513/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754513/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754513/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Assets: Departmental Coordination","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will establish a cross-departmental working group to implement consistent reporting standards across all asset classes and product structures.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","6380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754514","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-06","<p>It is important that pension savers know the costs and charges they are paying and the government is committed to making this happen. We want pension scheme members to have confidence that there are no hidden charges or fees being taken from their pots.</p><p> </p><p>Since 2015, we have required occupational and personal workplace pension schemes offering money purchase benefits, including master trust schemes, to produce an annual statement, which is available to members; which sets out the level of charges and, as far as they are able, transaction costs applicable to all funds; and the extent to which these charges and costs represent good value for members.</p><p> </p><p>It has previously been difficult for schemes to obtain information about the charges and transaction costs they incur. The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) consulted last year on proposals requiring asset managers to disclose this information to trustees of occupational schemes offering money purchase benefits, and the governance committees for workplace personal pensions.</p><p> </p><p>The FCA will publish a Policy Statement later in the year setting out the final rules and guidance to disclose costs in a standardised format. We then intend to consult on how we can provide information about these costs and charges to the members of occupational schemes and to publish it. The FCA will, thereafter, introduce similar provisions for personal workplace pension schemes members.</p><p> </p><p>The FCA’s Asset Management Market Study indicated that there are significant issues with the way the investment market works. Savers, trustees, and scheme sponsors need a transparent, competitive and cost-effective investment market to provide for their security in later life and to keep their pension provision affordable. We will be studying the recommendations and proposed remedies closely to see what else government can do to support the FCA’s vital work in this area, which could deliver favourable outcomes for pension savers.</p><p> </p><p>To drive competitive pressure on asset managers the FCA recommended we look at barriers to scheme consolidation. We know that smaller pension schemes may not be able to negotiate or drive lower prices within this market, which in turn can lead to better outcomes for savers. Following a recent Call for Evidence, we are actively considering ways that we can simplify scheme consolidation and enable pension scheme scale to develop further.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman","6008 ; 6009 ; 6011 ; 6012 ; 6381","2017-09-06T10:27:04.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754514/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754514/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754514/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-20","Pensions: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department is taking to improve the transparency of pension costs.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","6382"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754515","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-06","<p>It is important that pension savers know the costs and charges they are paying and the government is committed to making this happen. We want pension scheme members to have confidence that there are no hidden charges or fees being taken from their pots.</p><p> </p><p>Since 2015, we have required occupational and personal workplace pension schemes offering money purchase benefits, including master trust schemes, to produce an annual statement, which is available to members; which sets out the level of charges and, as far as they are able, transaction costs applicable to all funds; and the extent to which these charges and costs represent good value for members.</p><p> </p><p>It has previously been difficult for schemes to obtain information about the charges and transaction costs they incur. The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) consulted last year on proposals requiring asset managers to disclose this information to trustees of occupational schemes offering money purchase benefits, and the governance committees for workplace personal pensions.</p><p> </p><p>The FCA will publish a Policy Statement later in the year setting out the final rules and guidance to disclose costs in a standardised format. We then intend to consult on how we can provide information about these costs and charges to the members of occupational schemes and to publish it. The FCA will, thereafter, introduce similar provisions for personal workplace pension schemes members.</p><p> </p><p>The FCA’s Asset Management Market Study indicated that there are significant issues with the way the investment market works. Savers, trustees, and scheme sponsors need a transparent, competitive and cost-effective investment market to provide for their security in later life and to keep their pension provision affordable. We will be studying the recommendations and proposed remedies closely to see what else government can do to support the FCA’s vital work in this area, which could deliver favourable outcomes for pension savers.</p><p> </p><p>To drive competitive pressure on asset managers the FCA recommended we look at barriers to scheme consolidation. We know that smaller pension schemes may not be able to negotiate or drive lower prices within this market, which in turn can lead to better outcomes for savers. Following a recent Call for Evidence, we are actively considering ways that we can simplify scheme consolidation and enable pension scheme scale to develop further.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman","6008 ; 6009 ; 6011 ; 6012 ; 6382","2017-09-06T10:27:04.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754515/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754515/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754515/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-20","Pensions: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what plans he has to bring forward legislative proposals to tackle the issue of hidden costs in pension pots.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","6381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754516","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-06","<p>This is an operational matter for the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), who are operationally independent from Government.</p><p> </p><p>The question has been passed on to the FCA. The FCA will reply directly to the Hon. Member by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-09-06T09:16:16.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754516/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754516/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754516/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will hold discussions with the Financial Conduct Authority to bring forward its postponed 2017 review of the effectiveness of Independent Governance Committees in protecting consumer interests in contract-based pension schemes.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","6383"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754517","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-06","<p>We want pension schemes to take account of all financial long-term risks when making investment decisions, and we therefore welcome the Law Commission’s report.</p><p>We are concerned that some investment decisions may be made with short-term considerations in mind. This can exclude consideration of options that take account of longer term financial factors, such as those arising from material environmental, social and governance (ESG) risks.</p><p>We are concerned that some investment decisions may not appropriately take into account longer term financial factors, such as those arising from material environmental, social and governance (ESG) risks.</p><p>One of the key recommendations is for trustees and providers to clearly distinguish financial risk factors – which must be taken account of; and non-financial (ethical) factors – which can be taken account if certain conditions are met. We will consider afresh whether our current legislation is clear enough in light of the report.</p><p>However, we also wish to address some of the behavioural biases that may exist in the industry, such as the assumption that social motivation and good investment returns are not compatible.</p><p>In line with the protocol agreed by the Lord Chancellor with the Law Commission, we aim to provide an interim response to both the 5 recommendations and the 11 options for reform by December 2017. We will respond in full within one year of publication, by June 2018.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-09-06T11:10:35.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754517/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754517/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754517/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-20","Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what plans he has to implement the recommendations of the Law Commission on clarifying the duties of pension providers in respect of long-term investment factors.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","6384"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754518","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-05","<p>There are currently no plans for HMRC to conduct a review of VAT charges on cosmetic surgeries.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-09-05T07:52:07.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754518/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754518/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754518/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Plastic Surgery: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether HM Revenue and Customs plans to conduct a review of VAT charges on cosmetic surgeries; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","6364"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754519","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-05","<p>The Government published its response to consultation on the Green Paper on <em>Corporate Governance Reform </em>on 29th August.</p><p>The response sets out the Government’s plans to introduce secondary legislation to require quoted companies to report annually the ratio of CEO pay to the average pay of their UK workforce along with a narrative explaining changes to that ratio from year to year and setting the ratio in the context of pay and conditions across the wider workforce.</p><p>Companies already face a binding vote on their executive remuneration policy at least once every three years, and must win a binding shareholder vote for any executive pay proposals that deviate from that policy. Most listed companies secure strong backing from their shareholders for their executive pay arrangements and are sensitive to shareholder concerns.</p><p>A minority, however, do not respond adequately to shareholder concerns. The Government has therefore invited the Financial Reporting Council to revise the UK Corporate Governance Code to be more specific about the steps that premium listed companies should take to understand and address shareholder concerns when they encounter significant opposition to their executive pay policies and awards.</p><p>The Government has also invited the Investment Association to implement a proposal made in its response to the Green Paper to maintain a public register of listed companies encountering shareholder opposition to pay awards of 20% or more. This will be accompanied by a record of what these companies have said they are doing to address shareholder concerns. The Government will monitor the impact of these measures.</p><p>A copy of the Government’s response to consultation on the <em>Corporate Governance Reform </em>green paper can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/corporate-governance-reform" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/corporate-governance-reform</a>.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","6495","2017-09-05T16:27:50.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754519/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754519/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754519/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-20","Directors: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what plans he has to make executive pay packages subject to annual votes by shareholders.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","6496"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754520","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-05","<p>Treasury Ministers and officials have meetings with a wide variety of organisations in the public and private sectors as part of the process of policy development and delivery.</p><p> </p><p>Details of ministerial and permanent secretary meetings with external organisations on departmental business are published on a quarterly basis and are available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-ministers-meetings-hospitality-gifts-and-overseas-travel" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-ministers-meetings-hospitality-gifts-and-overseas-travel</a></p><p><strong><br> </strong></p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","6463","2017-09-05T07:45:46.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754520/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754520/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754520/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Treasury: Saudi Arabia","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the (a) date and (b) nature was of each meeting he or officials from his Department have had with representatives of the Government of Saudi Arabia in the last 24 months.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","6464"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754521","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-06","<p>Information on the Making Tax Digital (MTD) rollout was given in my written statement to the House on 13 July which is available here.</p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statements/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;use-dates=True&amp;answered-from=2017-07-13&amp;answered-to=2017-07-13&amp;dept=14&amp;uin=HCWS47" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statements/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;use-dates=True&amp;answered-from=2017-07-13&amp;answered-to=2017-07-13&amp;dept=14&amp;uin=HCWS47</a></p><p> </p><p>The Government’s changes to the MTD timetable, which will now see MTD phased in over a longer period, will ensure that businesses have plenty of time to adapt to the reforms.</p><p> </p><p>HM Revenue and Customs’ impact assessment, published on 8 March, will be updated at Autumn Budget.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-09-06T09:09:59.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754521/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754521/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754521/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Taxation: Electronic Government","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the cost of the Government's changes to making tax digital.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","6497"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754522","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-06","<p>The Government has raised the following from the sale of Government land and buildings in the following financial years.</p><p> </p><p>2010-11 £257,256,884</p><p> </p><p>2011-12 £617,322,479</p><p> </p><p>2012-13 £388,855,250</p><p> </p><p>2013-14 £311,519,975</p><p> </p><p>2014-15 £224,541,513</p><p> </p><p>2015-16 £973,430,475</p><p> </p><p>In the autumn the Government will be publishing details of Government land and buildings sold in 2016/17 including the money raised. Selling surplus land and property is an important part of delivering an efficient and fit-for-purpose Government estate. It delivers value for the taxpayer and supports local growth, including unlocking land for new homes.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-09-06T16:12:29.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754522/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754522/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754522/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-20","Government Departments: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much has been raised from selling government buildings in (a) 2010, (b) 2011, (c) 2012, (d) 2013, (e) 2014, (f) 2015, (g) 2016 and (h) 2017.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","6498"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754523","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-06","<p>There will be no change to the universal nature of the Winter Fuel Payment for the length of this Parliament.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-09-06T10:59:36.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754523/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754523/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754523/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-20","Winter Fuel Payments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the cost of means-testing the winter fuel allowance.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","6499"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754524","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Department has undertaken an economic assessment of the impact of a new runway at Heathrow at a national level, taking account of all areas of the UK.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Regions across the country should benefit from new destinations, extra seats and increased frequency of service created by increased capacity at Heathrow. Enhanced access to international connectivity will be important in supporting regional economic growth. In addition, for regions where domestic air connections to London remain crucial, such as Scotland, expansion will create space for increased frequencies and new links.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-09-11T08:55:37.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754524/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754524/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754524/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-20","Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment he has made of the economic benefits to regions outside of London and the south east of England of an expansion of Heathrow airport over the next three decades.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","6478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754525","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Airports Commission published growth forecasts for regional airports for the three shortlisted schemes. The Department has undertaken an economic assessment of the impact of a new runway at Heathrow at a national level, taking account of changes in connectivity across the UK and beyond, and which shows significant economic benefits of up to £61 billion.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-09-11T08:00:31.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754525/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754525/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754525/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-20","Regional Airports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the value to the national economy of flights from regional airports to Heathrow airport.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","6480"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754526","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Government’s latest estimate, published on 2 February, was that a new runway at Heathrow will deliver benefits to passengers and the wider UK economy of up to £61 billion.</p><p> </p><p>Regions across the country should benefit from new destinations, extra seats and increased frequency of service created by increased capacity at Heathrow. Heathrow expansion is also expected to deliver tens of thousands of additional local jobs by 2030, and while it is not possible to precisely quantify the impacts on regional jobs and GDP, expanding airport capacity in the South East will support economic growth in the UK’s regions.</p><p> </p><p>Nevertheless, as part of the consultation on the draft Airports National Policy Statement (NPS) the government was clear that further work was underway to update the evidence base, including revised aviation demand forecasts. The Secretary of State for Transport announced on 7 September that there is a need to conduct a short period of further consultation to allow this updated evidence to be taken into account.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-09-11T14:03:19.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754526/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754526/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754526/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-20","Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment he has made of the economic benefits to the UK of the expansion of Heathrow Airport.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","6469"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754527","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-06","<p>The latest forecast for the revenue raised by the Soft Drinks Industry Levy was published by the Office for Budget Responsibility in March 2017. It is available here: <a href="http://budgetresponsibility.org.uk/download/march-2017-economic-and-fiscal-outlook-charts-and-tables-fiscal/" target="_blank">http://budgetresponsibility.org.uk/download/march-2017-economic-and-fiscal-outlook-charts-and-tables-fiscal/</a></p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-09-06T13:35:51.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754527/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754527/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754527/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Sugar: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much revenue will be raised from the sugar levy in (a) 2017-18, (b) 2018-19, (c) 2019-20, (d) 2020-21 and (e) 2021-22.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","6484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754528","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-08","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring economic security for people at every stage of their life, including when they reach retirement. The Government is also clear that fairness between the generations must be maintained. We are committed to the Triple Lock for the remainder of this Parliament.</p><p> </p><p>Details of the costs associated with the maintaining of the triple-lock after 2020 can be obtained from the Office for Budget Responsibility’s “Fiscal Sustainability Report 2017” which is available at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://cdn.budgetresponsibility.org.uk/FSR_Jan17.pdf" target="_blank">http://cdn.budgetresponsibility.org.uk/FSR_Jan17.pdf</a></p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-09-08T12:53:16.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754528/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754528/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754528/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","State Retirement Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the cost of maintaining the triple-lock pension after 2020.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","6489"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754529","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Treasury keeps all taxes under review and engages with a wide variety of organisations to understand industry developments, including the beer and pub industry and public health groups.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-09-07T16:22:44.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754529/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754529/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754529/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Alcoholic Drinks: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of increases in alcohol duty on the viability of pubs.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","6490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754530","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-06","<p>The Chancellor keeps all taxes under constant review, announcing changes at fiscal events. Spring Budget 2017 announced that Air Passenger Duty rates for 2019-20 will be set at Autumn Budget 2017, to provide good notice for the airline industry.</p><p>The government will commission a report into the effects of APD and VAT on tourism in Northern Ireland. Further details of this will be announced in due course.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-09-06T13:34:42.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754530/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754530/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754530/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Air Passenger Duty: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans he has to cut air passenger duty in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","6508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754531","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-08","<p>The Government’s pay policy has always been designed to strike the right balance between being fair to public servants and being fair to all those, including public sector workers themselves, whose taxes pay for them.</p><p> </p><p>That approach has not changed, and the Government continually assesses that careful balance. The current assessment is that salaries in the public sector are, on average, comparable to those in the private sector with the additional benefit of higher pension entitlements in many cases.</p><p> </p><p>Further details were made available in the House libraries in response to a written question from the Baroness Neville-Rolfe on 19 July 2017.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-09-08T12:46:52.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754531/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754531/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754531/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Public Sector: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of trends in the level of pay of public sector workers since 2010; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","6558"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754532","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Government has previously consulted extensively on the impacts of abolishing Class 2 NICs and responded to this consultation at Autumn Statement. This response is available at https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/consultation-on-abolishing-class-2-national-insurance-and-introducing-a-contributory-benefit-test-to-class-4-national-insurance-for-the-self-employed. The Government published a tax information and impact note on this policy at Autumn Statement 2016.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","6551 ; 6588","2017-09-11T15:51:33.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754532/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754532/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754532/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","National Insurance Contributions: Self-employed","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the Government plans to proceed with the increase in the cost of making voluntary national insurance payments for the self-employed.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","6587"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754533","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Government has previously consulted extensively on the impacts of abolishing Class 2 NICs and responded to this consultation at Autumn Statement. This response is available at https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/consultation-on-abolishing-class-2-national-insurance-and-introducing-a-contributory-benefit-test-to-class-4-national-insurance-for-the-self-employed. The Government published a tax information and impact note on this policy at Autumn Statement 2016.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","6551 ; 6587","2017-09-11T15:51:33.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754533/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754533/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754533/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","National Insurance Contributions: Self-employed","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of the increase in the cost of making voluntary national insurance payments for the self-employed on (a) low paid self-employed workers and (b) workers with variable incomes.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","6588"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754534","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-08","<p>The Government routinely makes adjustments to public spending throughout the year and will deal with the cost of additional resources for the Northern Ireland Executive within our overall plans in this way.</p><p> </p><p>At the Budget we will set out the latest allocations for departments and the Devolved Administrations. This is routine practice.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-09-08T13:56:48.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754534/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754534/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754534/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Public Expenditure: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the £1bn of additional financial support allocated to Northern Ireland announced in the Government policy paper UK government financial support for Northern Ireland will be funded through (a) additional borrowing, (b) further spending cuts and (c) tax rises.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","6589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754535","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-08","<p>In line with their duties under equalities legislation, Ministers fully considered equalities impacts and implications when setting the Government’s pay policy.</p><p> </p><p>The remit of the Pay Review Bodies continues to be to provide evidence-based advice to help the government achieve the right balance between being fair to public servants and being fair to all those, including public sector workers themselves, whose taxes pay for them.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-09-08T12:51:49.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754535/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754535/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754535/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Public Sector: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what equality impact assessment on gender and other protected characteristics under the Equality Act 2010 his Department has undertaken with regards to the public sector pay cap; and how it has affected the remit of pay review bodies.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","6730"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754536","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-07","<p>The government fully supports the principles of better debt management and lower levels of problem debt. This government has a manifesto commitment to introduce a statutory breathing space that would give heavily indebted consumers a period of respite from enforcement action, and further interest and charges for a period of up to six weeks. Where appropriate, they will be offered a statutory repayment plan to help them pay back their debts in a sustainable way. We will outline further information on how this policy could be implemented in due course.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-09-07T16:20:55.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754536/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754536/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754536/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Debts","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the Government plans to establish a breathing space scheme for vulnerable families in debt.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","6591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754537","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-06","<p>Knowing who ultimately owns and controls a company is a crucial part of the global fight against corruption, money laundering and terrorist financing. The UK is leading by example and our freely accessible public register of company beneficial ownership went live in June 2016.</p><p> </p><p>Last year, the UK co-launched a ground breaking new initiative with the EU G5 for the systematic exchange of beneficial ownership information. Since launching the initiative, over 50 countries, including all of the Crown Dependencies and relevant Overseas Territories, have signed up.</p><p> </p><p>Building on the success of that multilateral approach, the UK is now pushing for multilateral agreement on a model of public country-by-country reporting (CBCR).</p><p> </p><p>It is important that there is a level of international support and co-ordination that leads to both domestic and foreign headquartered groups being required to report information for a comprehensive range of countries in which they operate.</p><p> </p><p>That is necessary to ensure that public CBCR meets its objective and to avoid the initiative distorting business decisions on their group structure and headquarter location.</p><p> </p><p>The UK is, as part of this, engaging constructively with the European Commission proposal for public CBCR.</p><p> </p><p>That includes the high-level aims of the Directive, and the more detailed aspects of the Directive that are alluded to in the question, on which discussions are still ongoing.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","6101 ; 6102 ; 6103 ; 6104","2017-09-06T09:07:51.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754537/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754537/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754537/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Multinational Companies: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans he has for the implementation of the provisions of schedule 19, paragraph 17, line 6 of the Finance Act 2016 on country-by-country reporting.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","6559"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754538","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-06","<p>HM Treasury publishes distributional analysis of the cumulative impact of the Government’s tax, welfare, and public service spending decisions at each fiscal event, the latest of which can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/597473/impact_on_households_SB2017_web.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/597473/impact_on_households_SB2017_web.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>The Government publishes Tax Information and Impact notes (TIINs) for all tax policy changes. TIINs provide an explanation of the policy objective together with details of the tax impact on the Exchequer, the economy, individuals, businesses, civil society organisations, as well as any equality or other specific area of impact. All TIINs, including those for the Budget 2016 changes to Capital Gains Tax, can be found here:</p><p><strong><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/tax-information-and-impact-notes-tiins" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/tax-information-and-impact-notes-tiins</a> </strong></p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","6549 ; 6550 ; 6770","2017-09-06T09:00:32.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754538/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754538/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754538/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Capital Gains Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what distributional analysis his Department has carried out on the decrease of capital gains tax (a) basic rate to 10 per cent and (b) main rate to 20 per cent excluding residential property and carried interest.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","6590"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754539","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-06","<p>The criteria used for the UK’s listing requirements are a matter for the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA). The government does not as a matter of course comment on FCA consultations and decisions.</p><p>The independence of the FCA is vital to its role. Its credibility and authority would be undermined if it were possible for the government to intervene in its decision-making.</p><p>The FCA published its consultation on a proposal to create a new premium listing category for sovereign controlled companies on 13 July 2017. Interested parties have until 13 October 2017 to respond to the new proposals.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-09-06T10:10:11.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754539/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754539/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754539/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Stocks and Shares: Foreign Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he has made representations to the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) on the regulatory criteria the FCA uses in determining the requirements on companies controlled by other governments in seeking premium status listing status on the London Stock Exchange.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","6592"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754540","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-06","<p>Statistics on R&amp;D are collected and published annually by the Office of National Statistics. The latest data available shows that in 2015, expenditure on R&amp;D performed in the UK was £31.6 billion – its highest level on record. This is the equivalent of 1.7% GDP.</p><p>Government will spend an additional £2bn per year by 2020-21, around a 20% increase in total annual government R&amp;D spending. In addition to public investment in R&amp;D – each £1 of public expenditure on R&amp;D leverages an average of £1.36 of private investment across the economy – many other factors encourage private sector investment. These include our competitive tax system and business environment – the government also increased the rate of business R&amp;D tax credits, providing £2.45bn of relief to 21,000 business in 2014-15 – and our ongoing commitment to improving the nations skills, including in STEM subjects.</p><p>Information on international spending is published regularly by the OECD and the European Commission is available online. The government’s increased spending signals that the UK remains committed to being at the forefront of global science, research and innovation.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","6548 ; 6731","2017-09-06T13:37:48.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754540/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754540/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754540/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Research: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of UK research and development spending for 2016; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","6593"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754541","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-06","<p>Statistics on R&amp;D are collected and published annually by the Office of National Statistics. The latest data available shows that in 2015, expenditure on R&amp;D performed in the UK was £31.6 billion – its highest level on record. This is the equivalent of 1.7% GDP.</p><p>Government will spend an additional £2bn per year by 2020-21, around a 20% increase in total annual government R&amp;D spending. In addition to public investment in R&amp;D – each £1 of public expenditure on R&amp;D leverages an average of £1.36 of private investment across the economy – many other factors encourage private sector investment. These include our competitive tax system and business environment – the government also increased the rate of business R&amp;D tax credits, providing £2.45bn of relief to 21,000 business in 2014-15 – and our ongoing commitment to improving the nations skills, including in STEM subjects.</p><p>Information on international spending is published regularly by the OECD and the European Commission is available online. The government’s increased spending signals that the UK remains committed to being at the forefront of global science, research and innovation.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","6548 ; 6593","2017-09-06T13:37:48.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754541/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754541/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754541/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Research: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what proportion of GDP research and development spending accounted for in 2016; and how that proportion compares with average national research and development spending as a proportion of GDP across the (a) OECD, (b) EU and (c) Eurozone.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","6731"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754542","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-06","<p>Since 2010, the Government have secured almost £160 billion in additional tax revenue as a result of actions to tackle tax evasion, tax avoidance and non-compliance. This includes more than £2.7 billon from offshore tax evaders, with action both at home and abroad.</p><p> </p><p>The UK already has effective legislation to tackle avoidance involving offshore trusts. We announced our intention to legislate further, making it harder for anybody to avoid paying tax on funds held in offshore trusts and to introduce tougher sanctions for those who fail to declare past UK tax liabilities on offshore interests before October 2018. The Government is introducing legislation which will raise over £1.5bn from non-domiciled individuals over a five-year period.</p><p> </p><p>The UK has been at the forefront of international work which has seen over 100 countries commit to automatically exchange financial account information. Furthermore, we have set up a register for trusts with tax consequences, we have introduced new civil and criminal sanctions for offshore tax evaders and those who help them, and since 2010, we have invested over £1.8 billion in HMRC to tackle evasion, avoidance and non-compliance.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","6461 ; 6462","2017-09-06T09:25:34.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754542/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754542/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754542/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Offshore Trusts: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans he has to introduce measures to tackle tax avoidance and evasion by people and companies through offshore trusts.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","6560"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754543","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Government has exempted the gambling sector (except for non-remote and remote casinos) from The Money Laundering, Terrorist Financing and Transfer Funds (Information on the Payer) Regulations 2017 (MLRs). The Government’s reasoning is set out in its consultation response of March 2017 and can be found here:</p><p> </p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/money-laundering-regulations-2017/money-laundering-regulations-2017</p><p> </p><p>As per Regulation 16(3)(c) of the MLRs, the Government will keep under review whether providers of gambling services other than casinos should continue to be excluded from the requirements of these Regulations.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-09-07T16:23:58.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754543/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754543/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754543/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Money Laundering, Terrorist Financing and Transfer of Funds (Information on the Payer) Regulations 2017","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether HM Treasury has exempted gambling services from The Money Laundering, Terrorist Financing and Transfer of Funds (Information on the Payer) Regulations 2017.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","6561"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754544","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-06","<p>The number of prosecutions for tax avoidance and evasion for each full year since 2010 are as below:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Prosecutions (Convictions + Acquittals)</p></td><td><p>Convictions</p></td><td><p>Acquittals</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>390</p></td><td><p>336</p></td><td><p>54</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>449</p></td><td><p>413</p></td><td><p>36</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>576</p></td><td><p>540</p></td><td><p>36</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>761</p></td><td><p>716</p></td><td><p>45</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>709</p></td><td><p>642</p></td><td><p>67</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>880</p></td><td><p>808</p></td><td><p>72</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>886</p></td><td><p>807</p></td><td><p>79</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) does not act as a prosecuting authority. All prosecutions must be authorized by the relevant independent prosecuting authority, which for England and Wales would be the Crown Prosecution Service; for Scotland, the Crown Office and Procurator Fiscal Service; and for Northern Ireland, the Public Prosecution Service for Northern Ireland.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-09-06T09:12:12.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754544/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754544/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754544/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Taxation: Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many cases HM Revenue and Customs has pursued to prosecution for tax avoidance and evasion since 2010.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","6732"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754545","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-06","<p>The government has not conducted a full distributional analysis of cutting corporation tax to 17%. This is because there is insufficient data about the income distribution of corporate shareholders and uncertainty about the incidence of corporation tax.</p><p> </p><p>However, it is widely accepted, including by the Institute for Fiscal Studies, that a significant proportion of the burden of corporation tax is borne by workers and consumers, not just shareholders.</p><p> </p><p>As with all tax measures, the Government has published a tax information and impact note (TIIN) for this measure which provides our assessment that there are no equalities impacts.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","6564","2017-09-06T09:23:14.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754545/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754545/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754545/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-20","Corporation Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what equality impact assessment his Department has carried out on the Government's plan to cut corporation tax to 17 per cent by 2020.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","6563"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754546","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-14","<p>In line with expert advice, the first step to identify other buildings of concern following the Grenfell Tower tragedy was initial screening tests on Aluminium Composite Material (ACM) cladding samples. These generic tests are identifying which blocks have cladding which is not of limited combustibility, as defined in current Building Regulations guidance. The independent expert advisory panel recommended further large scale testing of cladding systems be undertaken according to the British Standard BS8414-1 and classified to BR135, the standard set out in current Building Regulations guidance. The large scale system tests provide more information about how cladding systems behave in a fire. The large scale tests are now complete and results can be found at:<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/latest-government-large-scale-fire-safety-test-results-published" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/latest-government-large-scale-fire-safety-test-results-published</a></p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-14T14:38:15.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754546/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754546/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754546/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-20","Insulation: Testing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment  he has made of the effectiveness of the testing regime to establish the legality of cladding.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","6627"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754547","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-05","<p>Where local authorities have a regulatory responsibility the Government expects them to fulfil that obligation. Local authorities are, however, independent from central government and their accountability is to their local electorate. Decisions on service provision and expenditure are at the discretion of individual local authorities having regard to their statutory duties. Concern about the actions, services or decisions of any particular local authority should be raised in the first instance with the Chief Executive of the relevant council. If this does not resolve the matter satisfactorily then contact may be made with the Local Government and Social Care Ombudsman and further information can be found at <a href="http://www.lgo.org.uk/" target="_blank">http://www.lgo.org.uk/</a></p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-09-05T09:12:11.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754547/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754547/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754547/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-20","Trading Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he can take to require trading standards departments to enforce regulations.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","6371"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754548","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-13","<p>Under the National Planning Policy Framework (NPPF), local planning authorities should ensure that any Plan they produce is based on adequate, up-to-date and relevant evidence. This is tested by the independent Planning Inspector, during the statutory examination of a Plan.</p><p>The 2017 White Paper: <em>Fixing our broken housing market,</em> also set out the scope of Government powers and criteria for making decision on whether to intervene in local plan-making in exceptional circumstances.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-13T16:50:40.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754548/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754548/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754548/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-20","Local Plans: Leeds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what mechanisms are available to his Department to require Leeds City Council to review its Local Plan to take into account the Council's own downward revision of its housing target before it reaches public inquiry.","false","Biography information for Alec Shelbrooke","Elmet and Rothwell","Alec Shelbrooke","6422"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754549","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>We continue to be open to discussion with any local authority interested in voter ID pilots. We will make an announcement in due course once we have confirmed which local authorities are participating.</p><p> </p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-09-05T13:23:50.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754549/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754549/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754549/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-20","Electoral Register: Proof of Identity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 4 July 2017 to Question 2214, on electoral register: proof of identity, which local authorities his Department is currently engaged with.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","6728"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754550","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-12","<p>This Government remains committed to ensuring people always have a roof over their heads. We recognise that employment and social enterprise opportunities are key factors to help people avoid homelessness and secure a sustainable place to live and build personal resilience. That is why we have embarked on an ambitious programme, working with local areas and across government, to fundamentally reform the response to homelessness – putting prevention at the heart of this approach.</p><p>Part of this is our £50 million Homelessness Prevention Programme which will deliver an end-to-end approach to prevention across 84 projects working in 205 district and unitary local authorities in England. Some projects are actively supporting households into work in order to reduce the risk of them becoming homeless.</p><p>We have also invested £15 million to improve outcomes for young people through the Fair Chance Fund. This funding is turning around the lives of around 1,900 18 to 25 year olds with complex and overlapping needs, by supporting them into training, employment, accommodation and education.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-09-12T11:06:55.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754550/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754550/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754550/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-20","Homelessness: Employment Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to support homeless people into employment.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","6723"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754551","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-05","<p>My Department has not received any representations or reports raising concerns about discriminations against EU nationals in respect of access to housing.</p><p>Our policy paper, “<em>Safeguarding the position of EU citizens in the UK and UK nationals living in the EU”</em> published on 26 June, sets out the UK’s fair and serious offer to protect the rights of EU citizens living in the UK. This includes access to social housing for EU nationals.</p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-05T09:06:23.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754551/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754551/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754551/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-20","Housing: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether he has received (a) representations or (b) reports on an increase in discrimination against non-UK EU nationals in respect of access to housing on account of the lack of legal certainty as to the future status of EU citizens in the UK; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","6830"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754552","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Government's Housing White Paper '<em>Fixing the Broken Housing Market' </em>highlighted we would &quot;<em>take action to promote transparency and fairness for the growing number of leaseholders</em>&quot;. On 25 July the Government published two consultation documents relating to reforming leasehold. We are determined to rectify abusive practices within leasehold.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has invited leaseholder groups, charities and other stakeholders with an interest in leasehold reform to respond to the consultation and make their views known.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-11T15:17:38.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754552/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754552/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754552/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-20","Commonhold and Leasehold","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what areas of concern to residential leaseholders and commonholders his Department is investigating; what plans he has to address those areas of concern; and what steps he is taking to work with leaseholders' groups and charities to resolve their concerns.","false","Biography information for Sir Peter Bottomley","Worthing West","Sir Peter Bottomley","6784"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754553","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-11","<p>The policy for forfeiture of residential leaseholds remains with the Ministry of Justice and has not moved to the Department for Communities and Local Government.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-11T09:51:09.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754553/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754553/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754553/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-20","Leasehold: Forfeiture","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether policy on law and practice relating to forfeiture of residential leaseholds has been transferred to his Department.","false","Biography information for Sir Peter Bottomley","Worthing West","Sir Peter Bottomley","6785"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754554","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-05","<p>Where landlords have concerns about funding essential fire safety measures, they should approach us or the regulator, as appropriate, as soon as possible to discuss the position. Where works have been advised by local fire services to be essential to ensure the fire safety of a building, for local authorities we will ensure that current restrictions on the use of financial resources will not prevent them going ahead. The regulator of social housing can consider other options for housing associations. Any support offered would not include general improvements or enhancements to buildings which go beyond this. We will deal with any requests on a case by case basis.</p><p>Following a letter sent on 31 July to all local authority and housing association Chief Executives, my Department has been contacted by 27 local authorities to discuss the position on funding. The regulator of social housing has also written separately to housing associations. No housing associations have contacted the Regulator so far. It would not be appropriate to provide details of each case whilst discussions are on-going.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-05T16:54:41.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754554/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754554/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754554/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-20","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, which local authorities have made requests for central government funding to help with fire safety on tower blocks; how much funding has been requested in each such case; and how much funding has been approved or granted in each such case.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","6843"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754555","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-15","<p>No assessment has been made. However, the government has been clear that providing certainty for EU nationals in the UK is a priority.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-15T10:50:31.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754555/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754555/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754555/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-20","Housing: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of whether uncertainty around the future status of non-UK EU citizens in the UK will lead to discrimination in access to housing; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","6823"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754556","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Government set out its views in its 5G strategy that was published at Spring Budget 2017. 5G networks will have a role to play, alongside existing technologies, in delivering connectivity in rural areas, for example to support new use cases such as smart farming. The Government will use its new 5G Testbeds &amp; Trials programme to test use cases in both rural and urban areas, to improve our understanding of the economics of infrastructure deployment in different scenarios and locations, and how infrastructure can be deployed in a cost-effective way.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-09-13T12:45:31.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754556/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754556/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754556/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-20","5G: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what her policy is on the provision of 5G services in rural areas.","false","Biography information for James Cartlidge","South Suffolk","James Cartlidge","6816"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754557","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Department recognises the importance of sport to the nation and within that the contribution of international talent, and the UK will seek to continue to attract the best of international talent across all sports. As the Government considers the options for a future immigration system we will also need to understand the potential impacts of any proposed changes in all parts of the UK. We will look to develop a system that works for all in consultation with all relevant sport stakeholders.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","6787","2017-09-07T14:31:48.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754557/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754557/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754557/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-20","Sports Competitors: Entry Clearances","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions her Department is having with the Home Office on ensuring that transitional arrangements are in place for the entry of elite sports people into the UK after the UK has left the EU; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","6786"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754558","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Department recognises the importance of sport to the nation and within that the contribution of international talent, and the UK will seek to continue to attract the best of international talent across all sports. As the Government considers the options for a future immigration system we will also need to understand the potential impacts of any proposed changes in all parts of the UK. We will look to develop a system that works for all in consultation with all relevant sport stakeholders.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","6786","2017-09-07T14:31:48.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754558/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754558/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754558/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-20","Football: Sports Competitors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment her Department has made of the potential effect on (a) the football transfer market and (b) the entry of EU and non-EU players into the UK of the UK leaving the EU; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","6787"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754559","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-11","<p>The number of male and female staff on DCMS’ payroll at the following salary bands is as follows:<br></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Male</p></td><td><p>Female</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£100,000 - £124,999</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£125,000 - £149,999</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£150,000 - £174,999</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-09-11T11:37:30.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754559/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754559/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754559/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-20","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, if she will publish the number of (a) men and (b) women employed in her Department who earn over £100,000 per annum in bands of £25,000.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","6820"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754560","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Department recognises the importance of sport to the nation and within that the contribution of international talent, and the UK will seek to continue to attract the best of international talent across all sports. As the Government considers the options for a future immigration system we will also need to understand the potential impacts of any proposed changes in all parts of the UK. We will look to develop a system that works for all in consultation with all relevant sport stakeholders.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-09-11T15:28:02.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754560/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754560/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754560/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-20","Sports Competitors: Entry Clearances","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what consultation she plans to carry out with sports national governing bodies prior to the UK leaving the EU on the entry of elite sports people into the UK after the UK has left the EU; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","6781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754561","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-07","<p>While it is for each individual organisation to make sure they have the appropriate arrangements in place, Government continually evaluates security across the UK and taking the necessary steps to ensure the public’s safety.</p><p> </p><p>Additionally, DCMS attends the Tourism Industry Emergency Response Group chaired by VisitBritain. The group working closely with representatives across the tourism industry to ensure the appropriate steps are being taken.</p><p> </p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2017-09-07T11:14:23.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754561/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754561/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754561/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-20","Tourist Attractions: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment her Department has made of the adequacy of security arrangements at popular visitor attractions in the UK; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Margaret Greenwood","Wirral West","Margaret Greenwood","6833"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754562","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-07","<p>Government has published reports on the legacy from London 2012, with the most recent of these in August 2016. This showed that the Games generated over £14.2bn in economic trade and investment benefits, that Queen Elizabeth Olympic Park in east London is thriving and that the country continues to keep the spirit of London 2012 alive through community and arts initiatives established during the Games. The outstanding performances of Team GB and ParalympicsGB at Rio 2016, with both teams finishing second in their respective medal tables, shows that the public investment in elite sport developed in the run-up to 2012 and sustained since has paid dividends. The government's sport strategy, Sporting Future, aims to build on the success of London 2012 and make our country more active, with a sustainable and responsible sport sector, whilst continuing to excel on the world stage.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-09-07T16:51:37.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754562/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754562/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754562/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-20","Olympic and Paralympic Games 2012","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what recent assessment she has made of the legacy of the London 2012 Olympic and Paralympic Games.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","6722"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754563","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-11","<p>Digital connectivity is a clear priority for this Government. The Super Connected Cities Programme installed WiFi in 1491 public buildings with a combined annual footfall of over 114 million, including in Yorkshire.</p><p>BDUK’s Superfast programme will provide at least 24 Megabits per second (Mbps) coverage to 95% of the UK by the end of this year. In Keighley, superfast coverage is already over 95%.</p><p> </p><p>As a result of the Government's landmark agreement with mobile operators in 2014, each mobile operator will deliver mobile coverage to 90% of the UK's landmass by the end of this year. Additionally O2 will deliver indoor 4G coverage to 98% of premises in the UK, also by the end of 2017.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-09-11T15:16:19.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754563/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754563/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754563/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-20","WiFi: Keighley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what recent steps she has taken to improve wi-fi coverage in Keighley constituency.","false","Biography information for John Grogan","Keighley","John Grogan","6578"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754564","Department for Education","false","2017-09-07","<p>As announced by the Secretary of State for Education on 17 July, we will invest £100 million from the Soft Drinks Industry Levy in 2018-19 for healthy pupils’ capital. The funding will improve school facilities to support a range of healthy pupils’ activities, including PE and sports, after school activities and healthy eating. We are not planning to prescribe a particular amount of this funding to be used exclusively for PE, as we believe the investment should be informed by schools’ local priorities across this wider range of healthy pupils’ activities.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, we are doubling the Primary PE and School Sport Premium to £320m a year from September 2017 using revenue generated from the Soft Drinks Industry Levy.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-09-07T09:58:22.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754564/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754564/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754564/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-20","Physical Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what funding will be allocated to PE out of the Healthy Pupil Capitals Programme in England and Wales for 2017 to 2022; what the source of these funds will be; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mark Pritchard","The Wrekin","Mark Pritchard","6733"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754565","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-04","<p>The table outlines Arts Council funding for organisations in the Parliamentary constituency of Keighley since 2008/09</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2017-10-04T11:14:00.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754565/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754565/answer","PQ6568-Funding Data.xlsx","PQ6568-Funding Data.xlsx","Arts Council funding in Keighley","Arts Council funding in Keighley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754565/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-20","Arts Council England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how much the Arts Council has spent in each of the last 10 years in (a) Ilkley and (b) Keighley town.","false","Biography information for John Grogan","Keighley","John Grogan","6568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754566","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-11","<p>We are currently undertaking a review of gaming machines and social responsibility measures, which I announced in October 2016. The public consultation closed in December 2016, and we are currently reviewing the findings, which we will publish in October.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-09-11T15:51:08.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754566/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754566/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754566/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-20","Gaming Machines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what recent assessment she has made of the effect of gaming machines on levels of gambling addiction.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","6354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754567","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Government is committed to continuing to reduce barriers to switching, which is why the Digital Economy Act 2017, made explicit Ofcom's power to set general conditions for switching within the telecoms markets. Switching process should be led by the organisation with the most interest in making the switching process work effectively, the gaining provider. A Gaining Provider Led switching process is in place for customers that switch their fixed line telephone provider across the Openreach network, which covers the vast majority of phone lines in the UK and can take up to ten working days.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-09-07T07:30:36.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754567/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754567/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754567/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-20","Telephone Services: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what comparative assessment her Department has made of the (a) process and (b) length of time taken for consumers and businesses to switch fixed telephony providers and mobile telephony providers.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","6336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754568","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-11","<p>It is the Office of Communications (Ofcom) responsibility, as the UK’s independent communications regulator, to consider the costs and benefits of switching for businesses. The Government has made clear its position that the switching process should be led by the organisation with the most interest in making the switching process work effectively, the gaining provider. A Gaining Provider Led switching process is in place for businesses with up to ten employees that switch their fixed line telephone provider across the Openreach network, which covers the vast majority of phone lines in the UK. We are committed to continuing to reduce barriers to switching, which is why the Digital Economy Act 2017, made explicit Ofcom's power to set general conditions for switching within the telecoms markets.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-09-11T16:13:53.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754568/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754568/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754568/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-20","Business: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment her Department has made of the (a) process and (b) time taken for businesses with more than one telephone line to switch provider.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","6337"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754569","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-19","<p>The intention is to launch a campaign for a number of members of the S4C authority later this year, with new members in place by early 2018.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-09-19T14:20:39.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754569/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754569/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754569/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-20","S4C: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, when she expects to appoint new members to the S4C Authority.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","6444"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754570","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-05","<p>The number of male and female staff on DCMS’ payroll paid more than £150,000 is as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Male</p></td><td><p>Female</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Paid more than £150,000</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-09-05T15:16:15.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754570/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754570/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754570/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-20","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how many (a) male and (b) female members of staff in her Department are paid more than £150,000.","false","Biography information for John Grogan","Keighley","John Grogan","6566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754571","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-11","<p>We received more than 4,700 responses to the consultation on banning letting agent fees charged to tenants. We are currently analysing responses and will publish a Government response shortly.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-11T09:50:24.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754571/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754571/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754571/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-20","Letting Agents: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the timetable is for the Government's response to its consultation on the abolition of letting agents fee; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for John Grogan","Keighley","John Grogan","6571"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754572","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Listed Events regime is underpinned by UK law in the Broadcasting Act 1996. The government is assessing how the reciprocal recognition of the listed events between Member States will work after the UK’s departure from the EU. This will depend on the UK’s future relationship with the EU, but will not change while we remain a Member State. The government currently has no plans to review the list of events.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-09-07T07:26:52.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754572/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754572/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754572/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-20","Sports: Listed Events","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment she has made of the effect on the sporting listed events of the UK leaving the EU; and whether she has plans to review the list of such events.","false","Biography information for John Grogan","Keighley","John Grogan","6572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754573","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-11","<p>Ministers have regular discussions with the Director General on a range of topics including BBC presenter’s salaries.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-09-11T15:25:30.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754573/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754573/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754573/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-20","BBC: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions she has had with Lord Hall since the publication of BBC presenters' salaries on 19 July 2017.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","6574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754574","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-09-05","<p>As at 25 July 2017, a total of 26,697 Arctic Stars and 13,905 Bomber Command clasps have been issued to eligible veterans and their next of kin.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-09-05T15:05:37.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754574/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754574/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754574/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-20","World War II: Military Decorations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many (a) Arctic Stars and (b) Bomber Command clasps have been issued to date.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","6607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754575","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-09-05","<p>There is widespread admiration for the major contribution that the personnel of Bomber Command made to the Allied victory in the Second World War and their commitment in the face of significant losses.</p><p>Those who completed the minimum qualifying period of service in operational areas were eligible for the 1939-45 Star and those with long service in non-operational areas received the Defence Medal. In addition to the 1939-45 Star and Defence Medal, a series of Campaign Stars were created for participants in campaigns and many Bomber Command aircrew were awarded the much-prized Air Crew Europe Star or the France and Germany Star.</p><p>In his independent Medals Review in 2012, Sir John Holmes concluded that Bomber Command had been treated inconsistently with those who served in Fighter Command, and his recommendation of the award of the clasp to Bomber Command air crew is to bring this Command into line with Fighter Command veterans who were awarded a Battle of Britain clasp to the 1939-45 Star and thus reflecting the significant contribution both made to defeating the Nazi threat. The Government has accepted the recommendations of that review.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-09-05T15:00:45.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754575/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754575/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754575/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-20","Military Decorations: World War II","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will take steps for the issuing of a full medal for Bomber Command veterans.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","6581"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754576","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-09-06","<p>Between 2011 and 2013 the Government reviewed a range of options for RAF Northolt, including the potential for disposal or transfer of the aerodrome functions to a civil operator. As part of this, the Ministry of Defence (MOD) commissioned the 2012 Project Ark report. The reference to civil licences in the Project Ark report was in relation to some of these options. Following this review, in April 2013 MOD Ministers took the decision to retain RAF Northolt as a military aerodrome, and other options were not taken forward. Therefore, civil licences were not considered further.</p><p> </p><p>The Project Ark report said that there may be potential to increase civil use on the military aerodrome up to 20,000 movements. However, Ministers took the decision to raise the self-imposed cap on civil movements to 12,000 movements per year. There are no plans to revisit this decision.</p><p> </p><p>Following that April 2013 review decision, the Project Ark report was archived, many of its options remained hypothetical, and it is not an active planning document.</p><p> </p><p>Medium-size airliner type aircraft can be operated at RAF Northolt. Alongside the based BAe 146 military airframes, a number of European allies operate medium-airliner-sized military aircraft into RAF Northolt on military business. However, civil movements remain under strict terms and conditions which specifically limit operating hours and the number of passengers, and exclude Scheduled Commercial Operations. This has the effect of limiting the types of civil aircraft which can operate into RAF Northolt to business aviation flights.</p><p>No meetings have been held with commercial airlines about RAF Northolt, but Ministers did in late 2015 and early 2016 correspond twice in reply to the Chief Executive of Flybe, following an unsolicited bid from that airline. This was not considered further. There are no plans to change the strict terms and conditions that limit the number of passengers on civil movements and exclude scheduled flights.</p><p> </p><p>As the planned runway works will see the refurbishment of existing infrastructure for military requirements, and no change of use is planned, there is no requirement for planning permission.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","6451 ; 6455 ; 6525 ; 6527 ; 6533","2017-09-06T15:45:36.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754576/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754576/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754576/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-20","RAF Northolt: Aviation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to section 1.24 of the Project Ark report by Ernst and Young of 1 February 2012, for what reasons planning permission has not been sought from the London Borough of Hillingdon for the proposed works at RAF Northolt.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","6454"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754577","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-09-06","<p>Arrestor Beds have been installed at RAF Northolt. There are no other plans to install Arrestor Beds at any other RAF station in the UK.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-09-06T16:00:48.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754577/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754577/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754577/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-20","RAF Northolt: Aviation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether Arrestor Beds have been installed, or are about to be installed, at any RAF station other than RAF Northolt.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","6537"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754578","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-09-06","<p>The installation of the Engineered Materials Arresting System (EMAS) Arrestor Beds at RAF Northolt will give the RAF the ability to ensure site containment and safety in the event an aircraft overrunning the runway.</p><p>The EMAS Arrestor system, which will be used at RAF Northolt is currently the only product certified for use in the U.K. which has been scientifically modelled and manufactured to ensure arresting capability.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","6536 ; 6539","2017-09-06T15:59:15.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754578/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754578/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754578/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-20","RAF Northolt: Aviation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the safety benefits are of installing Arrestor Beds at RAF Northolt.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","6538"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754579","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-09-06","<p>The installation of the Engineered Materials Arresting System (EMAS) Arrestor Beds at RAF Northolt will give the RAF the ability to ensure site containment and safety in the event an aircraft overrunning the runway.</p><p>The EMAS Arrestor system, which will be used at RAF Northolt is currently the only product certified for use in the U.K. which has been scientifically modelled and manufactured to ensure arresting capability.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","6536 ; 6538","2017-09-06T15:59:15.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754579/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754579/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754579/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-20","RAF Northolt: Aviation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether the Arrestor Beds being installed at RAF Northolt are EMAS Arrestor Beds.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","6539"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754580","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-09-05","<p>There are no plans to replace revenue lost from commercial flights as a result of the planned closure of RAF Northolt's runway for resurfacing.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-09-05T15:07:12.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754580/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754580/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754580/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-20","RAF Northolt: Aviation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether he plans to take steps to replace revenue lost from commercial flights as a result of closing RAF Northolt's runway for eight months.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","6541"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754581","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-09-06","<p>Between 2011 and 2013 the Government reviewed a range of options for RAF Northolt, including the potential for disposal or transfer of the aerodrome functions to a civil operator. As part of this, the Ministry of Defence (MOD) commissioned the 2012 Project Ark report. The reference to civil licences in the Project Ark report was in relation to some of these options. Following this review, in April 2013 MOD Ministers took the decision to retain RAF Northolt as a military aerodrome, and other options were not taken forward. Therefore, civil licences were not considered further.</p><p> </p><p>The Project Ark report said that there may be potential to increase civil use on the military aerodrome up to 20,000 movements. However, Ministers took the decision to raise the self-imposed cap on civil movements to 12,000 movements per year. There are no plans to revisit this decision.</p><p> </p><p>Following that April 2013 review decision, the Project Ark report was archived, many of its options remained hypothetical, and it is not an active planning document.</p><p> </p><p>Medium-size airliner type aircraft can be operated at RAF Northolt. Alongside the based BAe 146 military airframes, a number of European allies operate medium-airliner-sized military aircraft into RAF Northolt on military business. However, civil movements remain under strict terms and conditions which specifically limit operating hours and the number of passengers, and exclude Scheduled Commercial Operations. This has the effect of limiting the types of civil aircraft which can operate into RAF Northolt to business aviation flights.</p><p>No meetings have been held with commercial airlines about RAF Northolt, but Ministers did in late 2015 and early 2016 correspond twice in reply to the Chief Executive of Flybe, following an unsolicited bid from that airline. This was not considered further. There are no plans to change the strict terms and conditions that limit the number of passengers on civil movements and exclude scheduled flights.</p><p> </p><p>As the planned runway works will see the refurbishment of existing infrastructure for military requirements, and no change of use is planned, there is no requirement for planning permission.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","6454 ; 6455 ; 6525 ; 6527 ; 6533","2017-09-06T15:45:36.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754581/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754581/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754581/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-20","RAF Northolt: Aviation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to section 4.22 of the Project Ark report by Ernst and Young of 1 February 2012, whether spare capacity at RAF Northolt can accommodate up to 20,000 business jets per year.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","6451"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754582","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-09-05","<p>The runway at RAF Northolt is a code 3 runway, which is defined as a runway of 1,200-1,800 metres in length. There is no planned change to the categorisation of the runway following the renovation works.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-09-05T15:02:13.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754582/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754582/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754582/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-20","RAF Northolt: Aviation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether the runway at RAF Northolt is a code 3 runway with a landing distance of 1,354 metres; and whether there are plans to change the categorisation of that runway as a result of the renovation works.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","6452"
