"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754687","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-08","<p>There are 22 air quality monitoring sites in the area surrounding Heathrow Airport, with monitors measuring a variety of pollutants from all sources. Emissions from aircraft are a ground-level air quality concern when the aircraft are below an altitude of 1000 feet above the ground. Therefore while aircraft do affect air quality levels in the immediate vicinity of the airport, factors other than aircraft have a greater contributory effect.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-09-08T10:43:23.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754687/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754687/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754687/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-20","Heathrow Airport: Air Pollution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the effect of aircraft on air quality levels in the area surrounding Heathrow airport.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","6475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754688","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>RAF Northolt is an operational military base and is the policy responsibility of the Secretary of State for Defence. In 2011, the Ministry of Defence consulted the Department for Transport on a range of options for the future of the base, but the subsequent decision to increase commercial aviation operations at the base – and any assessment of the impacts of this – remained with the Secretary of State for Defence.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-09-11T07:30:49.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754688/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754688/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754688/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-20","RAF Northolt: Aviation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions his Department had with the Ministry of Defence on the decision to increase commercial flights to 12,000 a year at RAF Northolt; and what assessment his Department has made of the effect of such flights on local air quality.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","6531"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754689","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-11","<p>Defra officials are having ongoing discussions with a range of industry stakeholders across the UK about securing the seasonal workforce needed in the future.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Following the decision to close the SAWS in 2013, Defra established the SAWS Transition Working Group, now called the Seasonal Workforce Working Group. This group meets regularly and brings industry and government together to monitor the seasonal labour situation across the UK. I attended the most recent meeting on 7<sup>th</sup> September, which included organisations covering the UK.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-09-11T16:20:16.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754689/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754689/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754689/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-20","Seasonal Workers: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions officials of his Department have had with industry leaders on the demand for seasonal agricultural workers in Scotland after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Kirstene Hair","Angus","Kirstene Hair","6425"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754690","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-08","<p>Subsidies are not paid to support shooting activities. Grouse moors are also used by farmers for grazing; specific data on payments to farmers who maintain grouse moors is not held as payments under the Common Agricultural Policy are made to eligible claimants on the basis of the area of agricultural land they own, not the activities which may take place on that land. Payments that farmers in moorland areas receive under the Common Agricultural Policy help them maintain our moorlands and deliver a significant boost for tourism and the rural economy in these areas.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-09-08T13:59:46.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754690/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754690/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754690/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-20","Agriculture: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how much was paid in agricultural subsidy payments to maintain grouse moors in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","6340"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754691","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-05","<p>Sewerage undertakers have duties to provide, maintain and improve a public sewer system to effectually drain their area. The Government’s draft strategic policy statement to Ofwat makes it clear that we expect the regulator to challenge sewerage undertakers to improve planning and investment to meet the wastewater needs of current and future customers, while protecting the environment.</p><p> </p><p>Sewerage undertakers must identify solutions that are most effective to carry out their duties. Replacing combined sewers can be part of the solution; elsewhere doing this would be prohibitively expensive. We continue to work with the industry to make sure that sewer overflows that remain an unavoidable part of such systems in extreme conditions are properly controlled. In particular:</p><p> </p><ul><li><p>Mandating monitoring of the vast majority of overflows by 2020 so their performance is understood, allowing water users and customers to hold water companies to account.</p></li><li><p>Introducing frequency triggers to permits for overflows associated with bathing and shellfish waters from 2017. This should ensure that, as pressures on sewer systems increase, their performance does not deteriorate.</p></li><li><p>Working collaboratively with the industry group 21<sup>st</sup> Century Drainage to develop tools to adequately address the highest spilling overflows.</p></li></ul>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-09-05T11:40:34.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754691/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754691/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754691/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-20","Sewers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps he is taking to upgrade the sewage system and phase out combined sewers.","false","Biography information for Steve Double","St Austell and Newquay","Steve Double","6432"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754692","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-08","<p>Alongside the publication of the Draft Airports National Policy Statement on 2 February 2017, the Department also published an Appraisal of Sustainability and Health Impact Analysis. The Department’s assessment of the potential impacts of a new runway at Heathrow on noise, air quality and health are set out in those documents.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-09-08T11:10:35.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754692/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754692/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754692/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-20","Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of additional flight paths at Heathrow on levels of (a) noise, (b) air quality and (c) health in local communities.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","6472"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754693","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-05","<p>The EU Ambient Air Quality Directive (2008/50/EC) has already been transposed into UK law.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-09-05T17:25:08.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754693/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754693/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754693/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-20","Air Pollution: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether EU Directive 2008/50/EC on Air Quality will be transposed into UK law.","false","Biography information for Zac Goldsmith","Richmond Park","Zac Goldsmith","6471"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754694","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Department secures advice on effects of air pollution on public health from Public Health England, and the Committee on the Medical Effects of Air Pollutants (COMEAP).</p><p> </p><p>Public Health England continues to keep the evidence under review. COMEAP has been commissioned to further consider the available evidence and will report in due course.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-09-07T10:40:48.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754694/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754694/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754694/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-20","Air Pollution: Dementia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent analysis his Department has undertaken of scientific evidence linking air pollution to dementia, and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Edward Davey","Kingston and Surbiton","Sir Edward Davey","6763"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754695","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-05","<p>The Government believes that effective pesticides should be authorised where the scientific evidence shows they do not pose unacceptable risks to human health or the environment. The European Food Safety Authority has identified no safety concerns arising from the use of glyphosate and UK scientists agree with that conclusion.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-09-05T17:15:30.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754695/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754695/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754695/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-20","Agriculture: Glyphosate","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what his policy is on the use of glyphosate by farmers.","false","Biography information for James Cartlidge","South Suffolk","James Cartlidge","6815"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754696","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-05","<p>Cleaning up the UK’s air quality and cutting harmful emissions is a priority for this Government.</p><p> </p><p>In July the Government launched the UK plan for tackling roadside nitrogen dioxide (NO2) concentrations. This will require local authorities to produce local air quality plans which reduce NO2 levels in the shortest possible time.</p><p> </p><p>In addition to our work on NO2 we will deliver an updated Clean Air Strategy in 2018. This will set out how we will work towards our international commitments to significantly reduce damaging emissions of five major air pollutants by 2030.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-09-05T17:07:27.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754696/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754696/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754696/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-20","Air Pollution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of developing an air quality strategy to improve the capacity of the Government to meet its air quality targets.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","6798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754697","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-05","<p>The Department does not hold information in relation to this request.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-09-05T17:18:11.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754697/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754697/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754697/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-20","Sewage: Boats","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate he has made of the amount of waste water being released from residential and non-residential boats.","false","Biography information for James Cartlidge","South Suffolk","James Cartlidge","6817"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754698","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-05","<p>Compliance with the Eel (England and Wales) Regulations 2009 is assessed against the provision of: catch data for eels less than 12cm long; recorded consignments of live eels from aquaculture businesses; and 60% of live eels (12 cm or less) placed onto the market. The Environment Agency 2016/17 assessment of industry compliance received 390 catch returns from 452 authorised fishers and is pursuing the remainder. All other data was provided.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-09-05T17:10:38.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754698/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754698/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754698/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-20","Eels","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent assessment his Department has made of the fishing industry's compliance with the Eels (England and Wales) Regulations 2009; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jon Cruddas","Dagenham and Rainham","Jon Cruddas","6810"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754699","Home Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>The Government’s policy paper (Cm 9464), which was laid before Parliament on 26 June, sets out our proposals for enabling European Union citizens residing in the UK before a specified cut off date (to be confirmed, but between 29 March 2017 and exit) to continue to live and work here. After five years’ continuous residence, they will be able to apply for UK settled status. There are no plans to differentiate according to work sector.</p><p>The details of the new scheme will be subject to negotiations. We will publish further detail on the specifics of the new application process, including detailed eligibility criteria and requirements, in due course.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-09-05T15:53:10.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754699/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754699/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754699/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-20","Fruit: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether EU nationals who work in the UK soft fruit sector will be able to continue to work in the UK after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for John McNally","Falkirk","John McNally","6779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754700","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-05","<p>The number of recorded actions taken against fly-tipping for both England and for Barnsley over the last seven years is set out in the table below together with the number of fixed penalty notices.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Actions relating to fly-tipping for Barnsley and England - 2009/10 to 2015/16</strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="2"><p>England</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>Barnsley</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Total Actions</p></td><td><p>Fixed Penalty Notice</p></td><td><p>Total Actions</p></td><td><p>Fixed Penalty Notice</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009/10</p></td><td><p>537,123</p></td><td><p>25,874</p></td><td><p>737</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>568,052</p></td><td><p>32,963</p></td><td><p>699</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>489,815</p></td><td><p>39,314</p></td><td><p>525</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>425,235</p></td><td><p>35,433</p></td><td><p>503</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>499,563</p></td><td><p>36,835</p></td><td><p>134</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>514,914</p></td><td><p>38,149</p></td><td><p>152</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>494,460</p></td><td><p>35,888</p></td><td><p>193</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>sourced from the Fly-tipping Module in WasteDataFlow which replaced Flycapture in October 2015</p><p> </p><p>Fly tipping data is routinely collected at a local level and collated nationally. The data is published annually on the GOV.UK website.</p><p>Local authorities adopt different strategies for dealing with fly tipping. Some have well developed procedures for issuing fixed penalty notices. Alternative enforcement options include prosecution, vehicle seizure, formal caution and warning letter.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-09-05T17:24:28.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754700/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754700/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754700/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-20","Fly-tipping","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many actions were taken against fly-tipping in (a) Barnsley and (b) nationally in each of the last seven years; and how many of those actions took the form of fixed penalties.","false","Biography information for Stephanie Peacock","Barnsley East","Stephanie Peacock","6686"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754701","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-08","<p>We remain deeply concerned about the human rights situation in Yemen. Regrettably, human rights abuses continue on a large scale. Conflict has had a significant impact on civilians. There continue to be reports of arbitrary detentions, the use of child soldiers and persecution of minorities.</p><p>The UK welcomed UN Human Rights Council's resolution 33/16.</p><p>We call on all parties to respect human rights in Yemen and support the work of the National Comimission in investigating abuses.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-09-08T11:26:46.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754701/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754701/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754701/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-20","Yemen: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what information his Department holds on progress made on UN Human Rights Council resolution 33/16.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","6752"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754702","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-08","<p>As set out in the response to PQ 4993, the Saudi-led Coalition have their own procedures for investigations, details of which they announced on 31 January 2016. We have encouraged the Saudi-led Coalition's Joint Incidents Assessment Team to investigate this incident, considering all the evidence available and to publish their findings.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-09-08T11:01:42.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754702/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754702/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754702/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-20","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 18 July 2017 to Question 4993, whether he has (a) requested and (b) been provided with evidence from the Saudi authorities establishing where the helicopter that fired on a boat carrying Somali civilians off the coast of Yemen on 16 March 2017 was made; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","6658"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754703","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-07","<p>Officials at our Embassy in Mexico City have expressed our serious concerns about the murder of Mexican journalist, Javier Valdez to the Mexican Government . We have supported calls by the EU for a prompt and transparent investigation by the Mexican authorities to bring the perpetrators to justice, and to ensure the protection of all journalists at risk.</p><p>The Government has also been clear in expressing its deep concerns about the Ayotzinapa case since the disappearance of the 43 students in September 2014, doing so most recently when Baroness Anelay visited Mexico in December last year. We will continue to monitor developments in both cases closely and press the Mexican Government to continue the investigations and support the families of those affected.</p><p>We have offered technical support to the Special Prosecutor for crimes against Freedom of Expression and the Deputy Attorney General for Human Rights to build their capacity to investigate such crimes.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-09-07T16:23:20.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754703/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754703/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754703/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-20","Mexico: Death and Missing Persons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to the Mexican Government on the investigations of the death of Javier Valdez and the disappearance of 43 students in 2014.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","6657"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754704","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Foreign &amp; Commonwealth Office (FCO) supports civilian conflict prevention and peace building in Armenia and Azerbaijan through projects funded by the Conflict Stability and Security Fund (CSSF). Recent projects have included financial support for mine clearing activities and independent news websites offering impartial news coverage in the South Caucasus. We are also engaged through our support to the Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe's (OSCE) monitoring mission.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-09-07T16:08:07.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754704/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754704/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754704/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-20","Nagorno Karabakh: Civilians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what support his Department is providing to civilian conflict prevention and peace building in Nagorno-Karabakh.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","6667"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754705","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-07","<p>The UK was concerned by the escalation in violence on 4 July that resulted in two civilian deaths and one wounded in the Azerbaijani settlement of Alxanli. The UK regrets the loss of life in the conflict and continues to urge the sides to exercise restraint and work with the Organisation for Security and Cooperation in Europe's (OSCE) Minsk Group to negotiate a peaceful resolution to the conflict.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-09-07T16:12:06.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754705/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754705/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754705/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-20","Nagorno Karabakh: Civilians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment his Department has made of reports of civilian deaths near the line of contact separating Armenian and Azeri troops in Nagorno-Karabakh.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","6666"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754706","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-08","<p>Boko Haram have led a brutal campaign of violence against civilians in the Lake Chad region. UK assistance is designed to help those affected, and assist Nigeria and its regional partners to tackle the threat. During their visit to Nigeria last week the Foreign Secretary and the International Development Secretary saw firsthand some of the support that the UK is providing. The conflict in the region requires a comprehensive response, tackling the threat posed by Boko Haram and the humanitarian crisis through the full range of security, political and humanitarian, and in the longer term, development work. The UK is a lead player, providing a substantial package of military, intelligence and development support to Nigeria. This includes training for the Nigerian armed forces and £5 million for the Multinational Joint Task Force, the regional force tackling Boko Haram. The UK was one of the first donors to respond to the humanitarian crisis in North East Nigeria and we have scaled up our support from £1 million in 2014 to £100 million this year. During their visit the Foreign Secretary and International Development Secretary announced an additional £200 million of humanitarian aid over the next four years.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-09-08T11:32:54.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754706/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754706/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754706/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-20","Nigeria: Boko Haram","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to support the Nigerian Government in protecting minority groups vulnerable to persecution by Boko Haram.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","6793"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754707","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-08","<p>The Government is gravely concerned by proposals to demolish the Bedouin village of Khan al Ahmar. Officials from our Consulate-General in Jerusalem have visited Khan Al Ahmar on multiple occasions in recent years. ​I understand that officials from our Consulate-General plan to visit Khan Al Ahmar before the next court hearing.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-09-08T10:51:20.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754707/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754707/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754707/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-20","West Bank: Visits Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he has plans for UK diplomats to visit Khan Al Ahmar in the West Bank.","true","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","Mr William Wragg","6399"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754708","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>​We are aware of a number of reports of Ahmadiyya being arrested in Algeria. We have raised this with the Algerian government, who said that the arrests relate to breaches of laws which apply to all religions in Algeria. The Algerian constitution provides freedom of religion and we encourage them to make domestic law fully compatible with that. The promotion and protection of freedom of religion or belief for all individuals internationally remains a high priority for the UK.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-09-11T16:57:47.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754708/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754708/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754708/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-20","Algeria: Ahmadiyya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to his counterparts in Algeria on the arrest and detention of Ahmadi Muslims across Algeria since June 2016 on grounds of practising their faith.","false","Biography information for Siobhain McDonagh","Mitcham and Morden","Siobhain McDonagh","6488"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754709","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-07","<p>Neither the Foreign Secretary nor I have recently discussed this issue with our Hungarian or EU counterparts. However, Foreign and Commonwealth Office officials continue to discuss the matter as part of our regular discussions with the Hungarian Government.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-09-07T16:14:37.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754709/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754709/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754709/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-20","Central European University","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with (a) the Hungarian Government and (b) his counterparts in the EU on the future of the Central European University in Budapest.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","6600"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754710","Department of Health","false","2017-09-06","<p>500 additional places have already been allocated to existing medical schools and will be made available for students commencing courses from 1 August 2018.</p><p> </p><p>We have consulted on how best to allocate the remaining 1,000 places by August 2019.</p><p> </p><p>The Government response to the consultation was published on 9 August 2017 and is available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/expanding-undergraduate-medical-education" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/expanding-undergraduate-medical-education</a></p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-09-06T12:07:22.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754710/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754710/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754710/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-20","Doctors: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the timetable is for increasing medical training places by 1,500; and what assessment he has made of the need for new medical schools as a result of that increase.","false","Biography information for John Grogan","Keighley","John Grogan","6570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754711","Department of Health","false","2017-09-08","<p>Smoking cessation services are a key part of the Government’s tobacco control strategy which is outlined in the recently published tobacco control plan. Councils will receive £16 billion of public health funding between 2016 and 2021 to provide vital services for their local population including smoking cessation services. Funding plans beyond 2021 will be the subject of a new Spending Review.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-09-08T14:52:07.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754711/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754711/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754711/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-20","Smoking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans he has to fund tobacco cessation services during this Parliament.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","6510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754712","Department of Health","false","2017-09-06","<p>In 2016, Public Health England (PHE) launched a mobile app in partnership with British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC) Get Inspired, based on NHS Choices’ Couch to 5K web site. The method of evaluating the effect and value for money of the Couch to 5K app in England involves tracking the number of downloads and conducting qualitative research.</p><p> </p><p>The app has received more than 500,000 downloads since launch<sup>1</sup>. The feedback from users is positive with many referencing the voice-over from popular coaches being especially motivating.</p><p> </p><p>The app does not record mobile sensor data and there is no historical app data available to compare pre and post usage.</p><p> </p><p>The app has been especially designed for people who have done little or no running. We hold no information on the activities of running clubs in relation to the Couch to 5K programme.</p><p><sup>1</sup> Source: Google Analytics</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","6692 ; 6831","2017-09-06T13:06:58.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754712/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754712/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754712/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-20","Running","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what information his Department holds on how many British running clubs have organised Couch to 5K programme since the inception of that programme.","false","Biography information for Nick Smith","Blaenau Gwent","Nick Smith","6486"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754714","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>Councils will receive £16 billion of public health funding over the Spending Review period to deliver local health priorities tailored to the needs of their populations. Tobacco control is within this remit.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-09-11T12:25:11.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754714/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754714/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754714/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-20","Smoking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much funding he has allowed for the delivery of the Tobacco Control Plan for England.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","6483"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754715","Department of Health","false","2017-09-06","<p>The following organisations were invited to the meeting on 20 July 2017:</p><p> </p><p>- The Haemophilia Society;</p><p>- Haemophilia Wales;</p><p>- Haemophilia Scotland;</p><p>- The Irish Haemophilia Society;</p><p>- The Hepatitis C Trust;</p><p>- The Tainted Blood Campaign;</p><p>- The Contaminated Blood Campaign; and</p><p>- The Birchgrove Group.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-09-06T13:55:28.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754715/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754715/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754715/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-20","Blood: Contamination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will list the people and organisations that those people represent who attended the meeting of 20 July 2017 to discuss setting up an inquiry into the contaminated blood scandal.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","6378"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754716","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>We have made no such assessment. Pharmacies on the pharmaceutical list, and thus eligible to provide National Health Service pharmaceutical services, are required to provide the same essential services and receive the same payment rates based on activity, whether they are internet or high street pharmacies.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-09-11T14:27:18.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754716/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754716/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754716/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-20","Pharmacy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the average cost to the public purse of dispensing a medicine through an (a) internet and (b) high street pharmacy.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","6404"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754717","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>40% of community pharmacies are in a cluster where there are three or more pharmacies within ten minutes’ walk. As part of community pharmacy reforms, we have introduced a Pharmacy Access Scheme to protect pharmacies in areas where there are fewer pharmacies and higher health needs, and to ensure no residents in areas will be left without good access to a community pharmacy.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-09-11T13:13:07.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754717/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754717/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754717/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-20","Pharmacy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of the concentration of high street community pharmacies in different areas of the country; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","6408"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754718","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>The future of the Pharmacy Access Scheme beyond March 2018 will be considered as part of negotiations with the Pharmaceutical Services Negotiating Committee, which represents pharmacy contractors in negotiations relating to pharmaceutical remuneration.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-09-11T14:18:03.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754718/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754718/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754718/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-20","Pharmacy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans there are to extend the Pharmacy Access Scheme beyond March 2018.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","6409"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754719","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>Essential services are available from all community pharmacies, which provide National Health Service pharmaceutical services in England. Community pharmacies can provide the following advanced services, if they meet the necessary requirements:</p><p> </p><p>- Medicine Use Review from 2005/06;</p><p>- Appliance Use Review from 2010/11;</p><p>- Stoma Appliance Customisation from 2010/11;</p><p>- New Medicine Service (NMS) from October 2011;</p><p>- Seasonal Influenza Vaccination from 2015/16; and</p><p>- NHS urgent medicine supply pilot scheme from December 2016.</p><p> </p><p>NHS Digital releases an annual General Pharmaceutical Services publication which provides the data requested. As essential and advanced services are commissioned by the NHS, rather than local authorities, local data is based on primary care trusts until 2012/13 and NHS England Regions from April 2013. The latest data available to 2015/16 can be found at:</p><p><a href="http://www.content.digital.nhs.uk/pubs/genphasernov16" target="_blank">http://www.content.digital.nhs.uk/pubs/genphasernov16</a></p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-09-11T13:59:27.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754719/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754719/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754719/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-20","Pharmacy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many NHS pharmacies have delivered (a) essential and (b) advanced services in each year since 2007-08 in (i) England and (ii) each local authority area; and if he will provide details of the advanced services delivered by community pharmacies.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","6407"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754720","Department of Health","false","2017-09-05","<p>National Institute for Health and Care Excellence guidance on antenatal care recommends that a discussion of mental health issues should be offered to pregnant women at booking (ideally 10 weeks). This is the minimum that commissioners should be contracting against with maternity providers. The Department does not collect data on the quality of mental health advice given by healthcare professionals during the antenatal period.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is investing £365 million from 2015/16 to 2020/21 in perinatal mental health services, and NHS England is leading a transformation programme to ensure that by 2020/21 at least 30,000 more women each year are able to access evidence-based specialist mental health care during the perinatal period. A key element of the programme is to increase awareness and skills across the workforce, supporting better identification of perinatal mental illness, early intervention and improved recovery rates.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","6447","2017-09-05T13:15:17.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754720/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754720/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754720/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-20","Pregnancy: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department has taken to increase awareness of perinatal mental health during antenatal classes.","false","Biography information for Gavin Robinson","Belfast East","Gavin Robinson","6446"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754721","Department of Health","false","2017-09-05","<p>National Institute for Health and Care Excellence guidance on antenatal care recommends that a discussion of mental health issues should be offered to pregnant women at booking (ideally 10 weeks). This is the minimum that commissioners should be contracting against with maternity providers. The Department does not collect data on the quality of mental health advice given by healthcare professionals during the antenatal period.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is investing £365 million from 2015/16 to 2020/21 in perinatal mental health services, and NHS England is leading a transformation programme to ensure that by 2020/21 at least 30,000 more women each year are able to access evidence-based specialist mental health care during the perinatal period. A key element of the programme is to increase awareness and skills across the workforce, supporting better identification of perinatal mental illness, early intervention and improved recovery rates.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","6446","2017-09-05T13:15:17.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754721/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754721/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754721/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-20","Pregnancy: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of mental health advice given by healthcare professionals during antenatal periods.","false","Biography information for Gavin Robinson","Belfast East","Gavin Robinson","6447"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754722","Department of Health","false","2017-09-08","<p>At the moment, only patients who have nominated a dispenser (community pharmacy or dispensing appliance contractor) of their choice are able to use the Electronic Prescription Service (EPS). Patients are informed about EPS, its benefits and are encouraged to use the service by both their general practitioner practices and dispensers. Patients are free to change their mind and nominate a different pharmacy or remove their nomination at any point. The next phase (Phase 4) of EPS will provide patients with a barcode that they can present to any pharmacy of their choice without needing to nominate in advance – thereby giving the patient complete choice of pharmacy. NHS Digital plans to pilot Phase 4 in April next year subject to the agreement of changes to prescribing and dispensing legislation.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-09-08T14:54:24.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754722/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754722/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754722/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-20","Pharmacy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to encourage choice of pharmacy at the point of an electronic prescription being issued.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","6412"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754723","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>Uptake is driven by the prescribing and dispensing communities, who realise many of the benefits of electronic prescription service (EPS) within their businesses and have a vested interest in promoting the EPS. They are being supported by the NHS Digital Implementation and Business Change Team who provide support to prescribers and dispensers of the service. The NHS Business Services Authority also have a programme of work to support the uptake of EPS in practices across the country. The other key strand of activity is the future introduction of Phase 4 the point at which all eligible prescriptions can be sent electronically and patients will no longer have to nominate a pharmacy. NHS Digital is also working with other care settings and their system suppliers, e.g. urgent and emergency care, to introduce the benefits of EPS into other areas of the NHS.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-09-11T15:27:12.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754723/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754723/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754723/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-20","Prescriptions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to support uptake of the Electronic Prescription Service.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","6413"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754724","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>The total number of items prescribed by the electronic prescription service (EPS) by calendar year is shown in the table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Calendar Year</p></td><td><p>Items Prescribed by EPS</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>From July 2009</p></td><td><p>1,217</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>84,467</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>483,814</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>6,041,620</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>28,050,691</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>107,964,073</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>300,927,787</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>496,312,923</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Electronic transmission of prescription (ETP) allowances paid to community pharmacies in England by financial year are given in the table below.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial Year</p></td><td><p>ETP allowances paid to community pharmacies (£)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009/10</p></td><td><p>25,309,658.85</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>24,706,040.96</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>29,144,101.71</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>31,243,930.18</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>27,836,025.45</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>27,342,329.35</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>27,258,611.10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>192,840,697.60</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The information in both tables is based on NHS Business Services Authority data, which in line with their records management policy is only available from 2009/10.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-09-11T15:25:00.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754724/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754724/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754724/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-20","Prescriptions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many items have been prescribed by the Electronic Prescription Service (EPS) in each year since 2005-06; and what the total spend on the EPS has been in each year since 2005-16.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","6414"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754725","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>NHS Digital releases an annual General Pharmaceutical Services publication which has data on the total number of community pharmacies, providing National Health Service pharmaceutical services in England, including high street pharmacies, as well as the number of wholly distance selling pharmacies, including internet pharmacies. Data for the latter was only collected from 2008/09. As NHS pharmaceutical services are commissioned by the NHS, rather than local authorities, local data is based on primary care trusts until 2012/13 and NHS England Regions from April 2013. The latest release, covering the period 2006/07 to 2015/16, is available at:</p><p><a href="http://www.content.digital.nhs.uk/pubs/genphasernov16" target="_blank">http://www.content.digital.nhs.uk/pubs/genphasernov16</a></p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-09-11T14:03:56.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754725/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754725/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754725/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-20","Pharmacy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the total number of (a) internet and (b) high street community pharmacies in England has been in each year since 2007-08 in (i) total and (ii) each local authority area.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","6405"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754726","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>Services under the community pharmacy contractual framework, including the Pharmacy Access Scheme (PhAS), are commissioned and funded by the National Health Service, rather than local authorities. The projected costs for the PhAS in 2016/17 and 2017/18, for December 2016 and then in each quarter up to March 2018, are given below:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>December 2016</p></td><td><p>January 2017 - March 2017</p></td><td><p>April 2017 - June 2017</p></td><td><p>July 2017 - September 2017</p></td><td><p>October 2017 - December 2017</p></td><td><p>January 2018 - March 2018</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>PhAS (£)</p></td><td><p>3,960,069</p></td><td><p>11,880,206</p></td><td><p>5,812,669</p></td><td><p>5,812,669</p></td><td><p>5,812,669</p></td><td><p>5,812,669</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>PhAS reviews* (£)</p></td><td><p>123,529</p></td><td><p>370,587</p></td><td><p>240,809</p></td><td><p>240,809</p></td><td><p>240,809</p></td><td><p>240,809</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total (£)</p></td><td><p>4,083,598</p></td><td><p>12,250,793</p></td><td><p>6,053,478</p></td><td><p>6,053,478</p></td><td><p>6,053,478</p></td><td><p>6,053,478</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>*These figures showing the cost of additional pharmacies being granted the PhAS through the review process are subject to update. They do not include pharmacies operating under local pharmaceutical services contracts, which return to the pharmaceutical list and are eligible for the scheme.</p><p>The community pharmacy funding package, implemented from 1 December 2016, is delivering significant savings - £113 million in 2016/17 and a further £208 million in 2017/18 – and making an important contribution to the £22 billion NHS efficiency savings. The PhAS is a key element of that funding package to support access where pharmacies are sparsely spread and patients depend on them most.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","6411 ; 6419","2017-09-11T14:10:45.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754726/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754726/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754726/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-20","Pharmacy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the projected costs are for the Pharmacy Access Scheme in each quarter up to March 2018.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","6410"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/754727","Department of Health","false","2017-09-11","<p>Services under the community pharmacy contractual framework, including the Pharmacy Access Scheme (PhAS), are commissioned and funded by the National Health Service, rather than local authorities. The projected costs for the PhAS in 2016/17 and 2017/18, for December 2016 and then in each quarter up to March 2018, are given below:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>December 2016</p></td><td><p>January 2017 - March 2017</p></td><td><p>April 2017 - June 2017</p></td><td><p>July 2017 - September 2017</p></td><td><p>October 2017 - December 2017</p></td><td><p>January 2018 - March 2018</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>PhAS (£)</p></td><td><p>3,960,069</p></td><td><p>11,880,206</p></td><td><p>5,812,669</p></td><td><p>5,812,669</p></td><td><p>5,812,669</p></td><td><p>5,812,669</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>PhAS reviews* (£)</p></td><td><p>123,529</p></td><td><p>370,587</p></td><td><p>240,809</p></td><td><p>240,809</p></td><td><p>240,809</p></td><td><p>240,809</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total (£)</p></td><td><p>4,083,598</p></td><td><p>12,250,793</p></td><td><p>6,053,478</p></td><td><p>6,053,478</p></td><td><p>6,053,478</p></td><td><p>6,053,478</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>*These figures showing the cost of additional pharmacies being granted the PhAS through the review process are subject to update. They do not include pharmacies operating under local pharmaceutical services contracts, which return to the pharmaceutical list and are eligible for the scheme.</p><p>The community pharmacy funding package, implemented from 1 December 2016, is delivering significant savings - £113 million in 2016/17 and a further £208 million in 2017/18 – and making an important contribution to the £22 billion NHS efficiency savings. The PhAS is a key element of that funding package to support access where pharmacies are sparsely spread and patients depend on them most.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","6410 ;